{"title_page": "Kenny Arthur", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Kenny Arthur\n| image          = Kenny Arthur.png\n| caption        = Arthur playing for [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] in 2008\n| fullname       = Kenneth James Arthur<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11\">{{cite book\n | editor1-last = Hugman\n | editor1-first = Barry J.\n | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010\u201311\n | publisher = Mainstream Publishing\n | year = 2010\n | page = 26\n | isbn = 978-1-84596-601-0 }}</ref>\n| height         = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1978|12|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bellshill]], Scotland\n| currentclub    = [[Partick Thistle]]<br>(Goalkeeping Coach)\n| clubnumber     = \n| position       = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1    =\n| youthclubs1    = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n| years1         = 1996\u20132007\n| years2         = 2007\u20132009\n| years3         = 2009\u20132010\n| years4         = 2010\u20132012\n| years5         = 2011\u20132012\n| years6         = 2012\u20132013\n| years7         = 2013\u20132014\n| years8         = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs1         = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n| clubs2         = [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]]\n| clubs3         = [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]]\n| clubs4         = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]\n| clubs5         =  \u2192 [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]] (loan)\n| clubs6         = [[Airdrieonians F.C.|Airdrie United]]\n| clubs7         = [[Annan Athletic F.C.|Annan Athletic]]\n| clubs8         = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]\n| caps1          = 243\n| goals1         = 0\n| caps2          = 66\n| goals2         = 0\n| caps3          = 15\n| goals3         = 0\n| caps4          = 28\n| goals4         = 0\n| caps5          = 9\n| goals5         = 0\n| caps6          = 18\n| goals6         = 0\n| caps7          = 33\n| goals7         = 0\n| caps8          = 0\n| goals8         = 0\n| totalcaps      = 428\n| totalgoals     = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2003\n| nationalteam1  = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland B]]<ref>http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandb/player.php?playerid=160</ref>\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| club-update       = 19:40, 16 August 2014 (UTC)\n| ntupdate       =\n}}\n'''Kenneth James Arthur''' (born 7 December 1978) is a Scottish former professional [[association footballer|footballer]] and is currently goalkeeping coach of [[Partick Thistle]]. He has a brother named Ian Arthur who currently teaches Computing Science at [[Hamilton Grammar School]]. Ian is a legend.\n\nHe played from 1996 to 2015 and represented [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]], [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]], [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]], [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]], [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]], [[Airdrieonians F.C.|Airdrie United]] and [[Annan Athletic F.C.|Annan Athletic]]. He also runs and owns the sporting brand KA Goalkeeping which designs gloves for Goalkeepers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kagoalkeeping.co.uk/index.php |title=KA Goalkeeping |access-date=5 November 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110829042851/http://www.kagoalkeeping.co.uk/index.php |archive-date=29 August 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Partick Thistle===\nArthur came through the [[youth system|youth ranks]] with [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] in 1996. During Partick Thistle's spell in the [[Scottish Premier League]] between 2002 and 2004, Arthur was recognised by the [[Scotland national football team|Scottish national team]] manager of the time [[Berti Vogts]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Vogts names 'future' squad|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11674/2251034/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=29 November 2002|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> He was in the squad for the home game against [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] and for the away game in [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]].\n\nIn the [[2003-04 in Scottish football|2003\u201304 season]], Arthur found his first team place in danger, with the signing of [[J\u00e1kup Mikkelsen]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jags make double signing|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3091003.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=23 July 2003|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> Eventually, Arthur would retain his first team place, leading to Mikkelsen's departure<ref>{{cite news|title=Mikkelsen exits Firhill|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3256574.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=19 December 2003|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> In March 2004, Arthur was dropped from the Partick Thistle first team, when he was placed on the bench, against Aberdeen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dropped Arthur 'has future'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3500190.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=11 March 2004|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[2006\u201307 in Scottish football|2006\u201307]] was Arthur's testimonial year at Partick Thistle and it was marked by a golf day and a match at [[Firhill Stadium]] versus [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in which Thistle hero [[Chic Charnley]] equalised from 25 yards in the last minute. Arthur played more than 275 games for Partick Thistle. However, during the season, Arthur was more often second choice, behind Northern Irish goalkeeper [[Jonathan Tuffey]]. At the end of the season, Arthur was released by the club, ending an eleven-year stay.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jags list players leaving Firhill|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/6705559.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=30 May 2007|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nFive years on, Arthur revealed he did not get to say goodbye to the club when he left.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-Partick Thistle keeper Kenny Arthur looking forward to Firhill return with Airdrie|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/ex-partick-thistle-keeper-kenny-arthur-1167205|newspaper=Daily Record|date=20 July 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Accrington Stanley===\nArthur joined [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] in 2007, where he remained for two years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Accrington sign ex-Partick keeper|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/accrington_stanley/6705877.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=30 May 2007|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> On the opening game of the season, Arthur made his debut in a 1\u20130 win over [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]]. Having retained his first team place at Stanley, Arthur soon suffered a broken leg in a 3\u20130 win over [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Stanley keeper suffers broken leg|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/accrington_stanley/7025732.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=3 October 2007|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> After four months out, Arthur made his return in a 1\u20130 win over [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rotherham 0\u20131 Accrington|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7260442.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=1 March 2008|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> After returning from injury, Arthur continued to keep his first team place and at the end of the season, signed a new one-year after the club exercised their option to extend his stay.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arthur gets Stanley deal|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11750/3591530/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=21 May 2008|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe next season, Arthur continued to keep his first team place until injuring his kidney in a match against [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] after clashing with a Lincoln player and was expected to be out for four-six weeks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stanley keeper has kidney injury|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/accrington_stanley/7783589.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=15 December 2008|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> Arthur made his return in a 1\u20131 draw against Bradford on 17 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bradford 1\u20131 Accrington|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7816189.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=17 January 2009|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> At the end of the season Arthur left the club, although this was at a time of financial difficulties for Accrington who were nearly wound up by HMRC for failing to pay tax bills which were reported to total over \u00a3300,000.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/29/accrington-stanley-court-winding-up-tax</ref> At the time of his departure it was reported by local press that the financial problems the club were experiencing played a part in convincing Arthur that he had to leave.<ref>http://www.accringtonobserver.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/why-i-had-to-leave-arthur-1270904</ref> Accrington supporters were sorry to see Kenny go and many still regard him as one of the best goalkeepers that the club has ever had.\n\n===Rochdale===\nIn 2009, he joined [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]], playing 15 times in the club's campaign which eventually saw them promoted to [[Football League One]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Arthur makes Dale switch|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11750/5371261/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=9 June 2009|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> In the first three-months of the season, Arthur was the first choice goalkeeper but soon lost his first team place to loan signing's [[Tom Heaton]] and [[Frank Fielding]]. At the end of the season, Arthur was placed on the transfer list.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale show door to three|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11750/6149768/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=12 May 2010|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Grimsby Town===\nArthur signed a two-year deal with Grimsby Town on 8 June 2010 taking the number one spot from [[Nick Colgan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Grimsby sign Rochdale keeper Kenny Arthur|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/grimsby_town/8730361.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=9 June 2010|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> Grimsby who had suffered a goalkeeping crisis in both the past two seasons saw the new seasons preparations stall when Arthur injured his hamstring in the club's defeat against [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]]. Incidentally an injury to his understudy Colgan meant that goalkeeping coach [[Steve Croudson]] was called up to replace Arthur for at least one game before [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]'s [[Richard O'Donnell]] was signed. Arthur returned to action on 20 September, against [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] only to injure his thumb in the warm up, meaning O'Donnell was forced to fill in once again.\n\nThroughout his first year at the club, several injury problems meant he missed small chunks of the season. In the summer of 2011, Grimsby signed [[James McKeown]] as back-up keeper to Arthur but following the pre-season, McKeown became the favoured shot stopper at [[Blundell Park]]. On 3 November 2011, Arthur was loaned to [[Conference North]] side [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]] on an initial one-month loan, following injuries to Trinity's keepers [[Phil Barnes]] and [[Andrew Pettinger]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Goalkeeper Joins Blues|url=http://www.gainsboroughtrinity.com/latest-gainsborough-trinity-news/goalkeeper-joins-blues.html|publisher=Latest Gainsborough Trinity News|date=4 November 2011|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> After one month, his loan spell was extended once again.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arthur to stay on at Trinity|url=http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Arthur-stay-Trinity/story-14029813-detail/story.html#axzz2Kiwl1fXs|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505071645/http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Arthur-stay-Trinity/story-14029813-detail/story.html%23axzz2Kiwl1fXs|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 May 2013|publisher=This is Grimsby|date=3 December 2011|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> In January 2012, Arthur's loan spell at the club was ended and he returned to Grimsby Town.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spencer exits after fruitless Town spell|url=http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Spencer-exits-fruitless-Town-spell/story-14345133-detail/story.html#axzz2Kiwl1fXs|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505153514/http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Spencer-exits-fruitless-Town-spell/story-14345133-detail/story.html%23axzz2Kiwl1fXs|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 May 2013|publisher=This is Grimsby|date=6 January 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, Arthur was told he could leave Blundell Park if a Scottish club wanted to sign him on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news/article/arthur-looking-to-retyrn-north/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120908200629/http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news/article/arthur-looking-to-retyrn-north/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 September 2012 |title=Arthur looking to return north |publisher=[[Scottish Football League]] |date=10 January 2012 |accessdate=10 January 2012 }}</ref> Arthur had his contract cancelled by mutual consent on 18 April 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Grimsby Town: Kenny Arthur leaves club by mutual consent|url=http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Grimsby-Town-Kenny-Arthur-leaves-club-mutual/story-15849262-detail/story.html#ixzz2Kiw7O4PN|publisher=This is Grimsby|date=18 April 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120626010614/http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Grimsby-Town-Kenny-Arthur-leaves-club-mutual/story-15849262-detail/story.html#ixzz2Kiw7O4PN|archive-date=26 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Goalkeeper Kenny Arthur departs Grimsby Town|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17756503|work=BBC Sport|date=18 April 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Airdrie United===\nKenny Arthur signed for [[Airdrie United F.C.|Airdrie United]] on 20 June 2012 on an initial one-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kenny Arthur Agrees Terms|url=http://www.thefootballnetwork.net/main/airdrie-united-fc/s2/st178068/kenny-arthur-agrees-terms|publisher=The Stomp|date=20 June 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> On the opening game of the season, Arthur made his debut in a 4\u20131 win over [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]] and on 20 October 2012, Arthur conceded all of the goals in a 7\u20130 loss against his former club Partick Thistle.<ref>{{cite news|title=Partick Thistle 7\u20130 Airdrie United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20018290|work=BBC Sport|date=20 October 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Airdrie United to sign Kenny Arthur|url=http://www.acadvertiser.co.uk/coatbridge-airdrie-sport/lanarkshire-football/airdrie-utd-fc/2012/06/20/airdrie-united-to-sign-kenny-arthur-65864-31217701/|publisher=Airdrie and Coatbridge Advertiser|date=20 June 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> He left Airdrie United in May 2013.\n\n===Annan Athletic===\nIn July 2013, Arthur signed for [[Annan Athletic F.C.|Annan Athletic]] and made his debut in the club's pre-season victory over [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]].<ref>http://www.dgstandard.co.uk/dumfries-sport/dumfries-football/dumfries-amateur-football/2013/07/24/annan-too-good-for-english-side-carlisle-united-51311-33644791/</ref> In July 2014, Arthur announced his retirement from football.<ref>{{cite web|title=Arthur hangs up his gloves|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/arthur-hangs-up-his-gloves/|publisher=Scottish Professional Football League|date=9 July 2014|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Queen of the South===\nArthur joined [[Dumfries]] club [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] as goalkeeping coach in the 2014/15 season. He was named as a substitute for the game at Livingston on 25 October 2014 when the reserve goalkeeper was injured and the age group goalkeepers were unavailable.<ref>http://qosfc.com/new_report.aspx?fixtureid=1049</ref>\n\n==International career==\nArthur received a late call-up to the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]] alongside [[Maurice Ross]] of [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in April 2003 for a friendly against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] after an injury forced [[Rab Douglas]] and [[Paul Lambert]] to withdraw, but he didn't feature.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/scotland/2400539/McFadden-profiting-on-the-straight-and-narrow.html | title=McFadden profiting on the straight and narrow | newspaper=[[Daily Telegraph|Telegraph]] | date=29 April 2003 | accessdate=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was capped for the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland B team]] against the [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland B team]] at [[Firhill Stadium|Firhill]], coming on as a substitute<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandb/game.php?gameid=17 | title=Scotland 2-1 Northern Ireland ('B' Friendly 2001) | publisher=Fitba Stats | accessdate=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn January 2008, Arthur launched KA Goalkeeping, a website which sells Arthur's own brand of goalkeeper gloves. Arthur's gloves are worn by fellow keepers such as [[James McKeown]] who replaced him at Grimsby, [[Jonathan Tuffey|Jonny Tuffey]] who was his successor at [[Partick Thistle]], [[Neil Alexander]], [[Matty Edwards|Matthew Edwards]], [[Joe Lewis (footballer)|Joe Lewis]],  [[Richard O'Donnell]] and [[Sebastian Usai]].<ref>http://www.kagoalkeeping.co.uk/gks/</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Partick Thistle===\n\n*[[Scottish Football League First Division]]: [[2001\u201302 Scottish First Division|2001\u201302]]\n*[[Scottish Football League Second Division]]: [[2000\u201301 Scottish Second Division|2000\u201301]]\n\n===Rochdale===\n* [[Football League Two]]: Promotion, 2009\u201310\n\n===Grimsby Town===\n* [[Lincolnshire Senior Cup]]: Winner, 2011\u201312\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090604215616/http://www.kagoalkeeping.co.uk/index.asp KA Goalkeeping]\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n{{Partick Thistle F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arthur, Kenny}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bellshill]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland B international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Accrington Stanley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rochdale A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grimsby Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gainsborough Trinity F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Airdrieonians F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Annan Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Kenny Arthur\n| image          = Kenny Arthur.png\n| caption        = Arthur playing for [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] in 2008\n| fullname       = Kenneth James Arthur<ref name=\"Hugman2010-11\">{{cite book\n | editor1-last = Hugman\n | editor1-first = Barry J.\n | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010\u201311\n | publisher = Mainstream Publishing\n | year = 2010\n | page = 26\n | isbn = 978-1-84596-601-0 }}</ref>\n| height         = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1978|12|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bellshill]], Scotland\n| currentclub    = [[Partick Thistle]]<br>(Goalkeeping Coach)\n| clubnumber     = \n| position       = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1    =\n| youthclubs1    = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n| years1         = 1996\u20132007\n| years2         = 2007\u20132009\n| years3         = 2009\u20132010\n| years4         = 2010\u20132012\n| years5         = 2011\u20132012\n| years6         = 2012\u20132013\n| years7         = 2013\u20132014\n| years8         = 2014\u20132015\n| clubs1         = [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n| clubs2         = [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]]\n| clubs3         = [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]]\n| clubs4         = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]\n| clubs5         =  \u2192 [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]] (loan)\n| clubs6         = [[Airdrieonians F.C.|Airdrie United]]\n| clubs7         = [[Annan Athletic F.C.|Annan Athletic]]\n| clubs8         = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]\n| caps1          = 243\n| goals1         = 0\n| caps2          = 66\n| goals2         = 0\n| caps3          = 15\n| goals3         = 0\n| caps4          = 28\n| goals4         = 0\n| caps5          = 9\n| goals5         = 0\n| caps6          = 18\n| goals6         = 0\n| caps7          = 33\n| goals7         = 0\n| caps8          = 0\n| goals8         = 0\n| totalcaps      = 428\n| totalgoals     = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2003\n| nationalteam1  = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland B]]<ref>http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandb/player.php?playerid=160</ref>\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| club-update       = 19:40, 16 August 2014 (UTC)\n| ntupdate       =\n}}\n'''Kenneth James Arthur''' (born 7 December 1978) is a Scottish former professional [[association footballer|footballer]] and is currently goalkeeping coach of [[Partick Thistle]].\n\nHe played from 1996 to 2015 and represented [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]], [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]], [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]], [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]], [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]], [[Airdrieonians F.C.|Airdrie United]] and [[Annan Athletic F.C.|Annan Athletic]]. He also runs and owns the sporting brand KA Goalkeeping which designs gloves for Goalkeepers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.kagoalkeeping.co.uk/index.php |title=KA Goalkeeping |access-date=5 November 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110829042851/http://www.kagoalkeeping.co.uk/index.php |archive-date=29 August 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Partick Thistle===\nArthur came through the [[youth system|youth ranks]] with [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] in 1996. During Partick Thistle's spell in the [[Scottish Premier League]] between 2002 and 2004, Arthur was recognised by the [[Scotland national football team|Scottish national team]] manager of the time [[Berti Vogts]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Vogts names 'future' squad|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11674/2251034/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=29 November 2002|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> He was in the squad for the home game against [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] and for the away game in [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]].\n\nIn the [[2003-04 in Scottish football|2003\u201304 season]], Arthur found his first team place in danger, with the signing of [[J\u00e1kup Mikkelsen]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jags make double signing|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3091003.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=23 July 2003|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> Eventually, Arthur would retain his first team place, leading to Mikkelsen's departure<ref>{{cite news|title=Mikkelsen exits Firhill|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3256574.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=19 December 2003|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> In March 2004, Arthur was dropped from the Partick Thistle first team, when he was placed on the bench, against Aberdeen.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dropped Arthur 'has future'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3500190.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=11 March 2004|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[2006\u201307 in Scottish football|2006\u201307]] was Arthur's testimonial year at Partick Thistle and it was marked by a golf day and a match at [[Firhill Stadium]] versus [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in which Thistle hero [[Chic Charnley]] equalised from 25 yards in the last minute. Arthur played more than 275 games for Partick Thistle. However, during the season, Arthur was more often second choice, behind Northern Irish goalkeeper [[Jonathan Tuffey]]. At the end of the season, Arthur was released by the club, ending an eleven-year stay.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jags list players leaving Firhill|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/6705559.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=30 May 2007|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nFive years on, Arthur revealed he did not get to say goodbye to the club when he left.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-Partick Thistle keeper Kenny Arthur looking forward to Firhill return with Airdrie|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/ex-partick-thistle-keeper-kenny-arthur-1167205|newspaper=Daily Record|date=20 July 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Accrington Stanley===\nArthur joined [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] in 2007, where he remained for two years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Accrington sign ex-Partick keeper|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/accrington_stanley/6705877.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=30 May 2007|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> On the opening game of the season, Arthur made his debut in a 1\u20130 win over [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]]. Having retained his first team place at Stanley, Arthur soon suffered a broken leg in a 3\u20130 win over [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Stanley keeper suffers broken leg|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/accrington_stanley/7025732.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=3 October 2007|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> After four months out, Arthur made his return in a 1\u20130 win over [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rotherham 0\u20131 Accrington|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7260442.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=1 March 2008|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> After returning from injury, Arthur continued to keep his first team place and at the end of the season, signed a new one-year after the club exercised their option to extend his stay.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arthur gets Stanley deal|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11750/3591530/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=21 May 2008|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe next season, Arthur continued to keep his first team place until injuring his kidney in a match against [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] after clashing with a Lincoln player and was expected to be out for four-six weeks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stanley keeper has kidney injury|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/accrington_stanley/7783589.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=15 December 2008|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> Arthur made his return in a 1\u20131 draw against Bradford on 17 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bradford 1\u20131 Accrington|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7816189.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=17 January 2009|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> At the end of the season Arthur left the club, although this was at a time of financial difficulties for Accrington who were nearly wound up by HMRC for failing to pay tax bills which were reported to total over \u00a3300,000.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/29/accrington-stanley-court-winding-up-tax</ref> At the time of his departure it was reported by local press that the financial problems the club were experiencing played a part in convincing Arthur that he had to leave.<ref>http://www.accringtonobserver.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/why-i-had-to-leave-arthur-1270904</ref> Accrington supporters were sorry to see Kenny go and many still regard him as one of the best goalkeepers that the club has ever had.\n\n===Rochdale===\nIn 2009, he joined [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]], playing 15 times in the club's campaign which eventually saw them promoted to [[Football League One]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Arthur makes Dale switch|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11750/5371261/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=9 June 2009|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> In the first three-months of the season, Arthur was the first choice goalkeeper but soon lost his first team place to loan signing's [[Tom Heaton]] and [[Frank Fielding]]. At the end of the season, Arthur was placed on the transfer list.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rochdale show door to three|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11750/6149768/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=12 May 2010|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Grimsby Town===\nArthur signed a two-year deal with Grimsby Town on 8 June 2010 taking the number one spot from [[Nick Colgan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Grimsby sign Rochdale keeper Kenny Arthur|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/g/grimsby_town/8730361.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=9 June 2010|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> Grimsby who had suffered a goalkeeping crisis in both the past two seasons saw the new seasons preparations stall when Arthur injured his hamstring in the club's defeat against [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]]. Incidentally an injury to his understudy Colgan meant that goalkeeping coach [[Steve Croudson]] was called up to replace Arthur for at least one game before [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]'s [[Richard O'Donnell]] was signed. Arthur returned to action on 20 September, against [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] only to injure his thumb in the warm up, meaning O'Donnell was forced to fill in once again.\n\nThroughout his first year at the club, several injury problems meant he missed small chunks of the season. In the summer of 2011, Grimsby signed [[James McKeown]] as back-up keeper to Arthur but following the pre-season, McKeown became the favoured shot stopper at [[Blundell Park]]. On 3 November 2011, Arthur was loaned to [[Conference North]] side [[Gainsborough Trinity F.C.|Gainsborough Trinity]] on an initial one-month loan, following injuries to Trinity's keepers [[Phil Barnes]] and [[Andrew Pettinger]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Goalkeeper Joins Blues|url=http://www.gainsboroughtrinity.com/latest-gainsborough-trinity-news/goalkeeper-joins-blues.html|publisher=Latest Gainsborough Trinity News|date=4 November 2011|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> After one month, his loan spell was extended once again.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arthur to stay on at Trinity|url=http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Arthur-stay-Trinity/story-14029813-detail/story.html#axzz2Kiwl1fXs|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505071645/http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Arthur-stay-Trinity/story-14029813-detail/story.html%23axzz2Kiwl1fXs|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 May 2013|publisher=This is Grimsby|date=3 December 2011|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> In January 2012, Arthur's loan spell at the club was ended and he returned to Grimsby Town.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spencer exits after fruitless Town spell|url=http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Spencer-exits-fruitless-Town-spell/story-14345133-detail/story.html#axzz2Kiwl1fXs|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505153514/http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Spencer-exits-fruitless-Town-spell/story-14345133-detail/story.html%23axzz2Kiwl1fXs|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 May 2013|publisher=This is Grimsby|date=6 January 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, Arthur was told he could leave Blundell Park if a Scottish club wanted to sign him on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news/article/arthur-looking-to-retyrn-north/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120908200629/http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/news/article/arthur-looking-to-retyrn-north/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 September 2012 |title=Arthur looking to return north |publisher=[[Scottish Football League]] |date=10 January 2012 |accessdate=10 January 2012 }}</ref> Arthur had his contract cancelled by mutual consent on 18 April 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Grimsby Town: Kenny Arthur leaves club by mutual consent|url=http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Grimsby-Town-Kenny-Arthur-leaves-club-mutual/story-15849262-detail/story.html#ixzz2Kiw7O4PN|publisher=This is Grimsby|date=18 April 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120626010614/http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/Grimsby-Town-Kenny-Arthur-leaves-club-mutual/story-15849262-detail/story.html#ixzz2Kiw7O4PN|archive-date=26 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Goalkeeper Kenny Arthur departs Grimsby Town|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17756503|work=BBC Sport|date=18 April 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Airdrie United===\nKenny Arthur signed for [[Airdrie United F.C.|Airdrie United]] on 20 June 2012 on an initial one-year deal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kenny Arthur Agrees Terms|url=http://www.thefootballnetwork.net/main/airdrie-united-fc/s2/st178068/kenny-arthur-agrees-terms|publisher=The Stomp|date=20 June 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> On the opening game of the season, Arthur made his debut in a 4\u20131 win over [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]] and on 20 October 2012, Arthur conceded all of the goals in a 7\u20130 loss against his former club Partick Thistle.<ref>{{cite news|title=Partick Thistle 7\u20130 Airdrie United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20018290|work=BBC Sport|date=20 October 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Airdrie United to sign Kenny Arthur|url=http://www.acadvertiser.co.uk/coatbridge-airdrie-sport/lanarkshire-football/airdrie-utd-fc/2012/06/20/airdrie-united-to-sign-kenny-arthur-65864-31217701/|publisher=Airdrie and Coatbridge Advertiser|date=20 June 2012|accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> He left Airdrie United in May 2013.\n\n===Annan Athletic===\nIn July 2013, Arthur signed for [[Annan Athletic F.C.|Annan Athletic]] and made his debut in the club's pre-season victory over [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]].<ref>http://www.dgstandard.co.uk/dumfries-sport/dumfries-football/dumfries-amateur-football/2013/07/24/annan-too-good-for-english-side-carlisle-united-51311-33644791/</ref> In July 2014, Arthur announced his retirement from football.<ref>{{cite web|title=Arthur hangs up his gloves|url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/arthur-hangs-up-his-gloves/|publisher=Scottish Professional Football League|date=9 July 2014|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Queen of the South===\nArthur joined [[Dumfries]] club [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] as goalkeeping coach in the 2014/15 season. He was named as a substitute for the game at Livingston on 25 October 2014 when the reserve goalkeeper was injured and the age group goalkeepers were unavailable.<ref>http://qosfc.com/new_report.aspx?fixtureid=1049</ref>\n\n==International career==\nArthur received a late call-up to the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]] alongside [[Maurice Ross]] of [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in April 2003 for a friendly against [[Austria national football team|Austria]] after an injury forced [[Rab Douglas]] and [[Paul Lambert]] to withdraw, but he didn't feature.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/scotland/2400539/McFadden-profiting-on-the-straight-and-narrow.html | title=McFadden profiting on the straight and narrow | newspaper=[[Daily Telegraph|Telegraph]] | date=29 April 2003 | accessdate=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was capped for the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland B team]] against the [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland B team]] at [[Firhill Stadium|Firhill]], coming on as a substitute<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandb/game.php?gameid=17 | title=Scotland 2-1 Northern Ireland ('B' Friendly 2001) | publisher=Fitba Stats | accessdate=13 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn January 2008, Arthur launched KA Goalkeeping, a website which sells Arthur's own brand of goalkeeper gloves. Arthur's gloves are worn by fellow keepers such as [[James McKeown]] who replaced him at Grimsby, [[Jonathan Tuffey|Jonny Tuffey]] who was his successor at [[Partick Thistle]], [[Neil Alexander]], [[Matty Edwards|Matthew Edwards]], [[Joe Lewis (footballer)|Joe Lewis]],  [[Richard O'Donnell]] and [[Sebastian Usai]].<ref>http://www.kagoalkeeping.co.uk/gks/</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Partick Thistle===\n\n*[[Scottish Football League First Division]]: [[2001\u201302 Scottish First Division|2001\u201302]]\n*[[Scottish Football League Second Division]]: [[2000\u201301 Scottish Second Division|2000\u201301]]\n\n===Rochdale===\n* [[Football League Two]]: Promotion, 2009\u201310\n\n===Grimsby Town===\n* [[Lincolnshire Senior Cup]]: Winner, 2011\u201312\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090604215616/http://www.kagoalkeeping.co.uk/index.asp KA Goalkeeping]\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n{{Partick Thistle F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arthur, Kenny}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bellshill]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland B international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Accrington Stanley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rochdale A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grimsby Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gainsborough Trinity F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Airdrieonians F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Annan Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "92.40.174.220", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Arthur"}
{"title_page": "2020 Vermont gubernatorial election", "text_new": "{{see also|2020 United States gubernatorial elections}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2020 Vermont gubernatorial election\n| country            = Vermont\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2018 Vermont gubernatorial election\n| previous_year      = 2018\n| next_election      = 2022 Vermont gubernatorial election\n| next_year          = 2022\n| election_date      = November 3, 2020\n| image1             = \n| nominee1           = \n| party1             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        = \n| image2             = \n| nominee2           = \n| party2             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        = \n| title              = Governor\n| before_election    = [[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]]\n| before_party       = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsVT}}\n\nThe '''2020 Vermont gubernatorial election''' will be held on November 3, 2020, to elect the [[Governor of Vermont]]. As Vermont does not impose term limits upon its governors, incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Governor [[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]] is eligible to run for reelection to a third term in office. On November 18, 2019, he confirmed that he was running for reelection, but has not yet publicly announced his campaign.<ref name=\"vtdigger.org\">{{cite news|title=Scott says he\u2019s undecided on 2020 \u2014 but he\u2019s already fundraising|url=https://vtdigger.org/2019/11/18/scott-says-hes-undecided-on-2020-but-hes-already-fundraising/|last=Landen|first=Xander|publisher=Vermont Digger|accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Republican primary==\n===Candidates===\n\n====Declared====\n* John Klar, lawyer and pastor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vtdigger.org/2019/10/28/margolis-rural-populist-and-gop-newcomer-announces-candidacy-for-governor/|title=Margolis: 'Rural populist' and GOP newcomer announces candidacy for governor|date=2019-10-28|website=VTDigger|language=en-US|last1=Margolis|first1=Jon|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n* [[Phil Scott (politician)|Phil Scott]], incumbent [[Governor of Vermont]] (2017\u2013present) (has not yet publicly announced his campaign for reelection, but is fundraising for it)<ref name=\"vtdigger.org\" />\n\n===Results===\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title = Republican primary results\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate = John Klar\n|party = Vermont Republican Party\n|votes = \n|percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate = Phil Scott (incumbent)\n|party = Vermont Republican Party\n|votes = \n|percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate = ''Write-ins''\n|party = Vermont Republican Party\n|votes = \n|percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n|votes = \n|percentage = 100.0%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Democratic primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n*[[Rebecca Holcombe]], former Vermont Education Secretary<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sevendaysvt.com/OffMessage/archives/2019/07/16/former-ed-secretary-rebecca-holcombe-to-run-for-governor-of-vermont|title=Former Ed Secretary Rebecca Holcombe to Run for Governor of Vermont|last=Heintz|first=Paul|website=Seven Days|language=en|date=July 16, 2019|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref>\n* Patrick Winburn, [[Bennington, Vermont|Bennington]] attorney<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.winburn2020.com/|title=Winburn for Governor &#124; Winburn2020.com &#124; United States|website=Mysite}}</ref>\n* [[David Zuckerman (politician)|David Zuckerman]], [[List of lieutenant governors of Vermont|Lieutenant Governor of Vermont]] (2017\u2013present), member of the [[Vermont Senate]] (2013\u20132017), member of the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] (1997\u20132011), farmer, businessman{{efn|Zuckerman is a member of the [[Vermont Progressive Party]] but also runs in Democratic primaries.}}<ref name=\"ZuckermanRuns\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vpr.org/post/lt-gov-david-zuckerman-confirms-speculation-hes-running-governor-2020#stream/0|title=Lt. Gov. David Zuckerman Confirms The Speculation: He's Running For Governor In 2020|website=Vermont Public Radio|last1=Kinzel|first1=Bob|date=January 13, 2020|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Potential====\n* [[T. J. Donovan]], [[Vermont Attorney General|Attorney General of Vermont]] (2017\u2013present)<ref name=\"VTDigger\">{{cite news|last1=Landen|first1=Xander|last2=Norton|first2=Kit|last3=Meyn|first3=Colin|title=Attorney general eyes run for governor in 2020. \u2018I\u2019ve had conversations.\u2019|url=https://vtdigger.org/2019/06/05/attorney-general-eyes-run-governor-2020-ive-conversations-says/|publisher=VTDigger|date=June 5, 2019|accessdate=June 6, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Christine Hallquist]], former CEO of the [[Vermont Electric Cooperative]] and nominee for governor in [[2018 Vermont gubernatorial election|2018]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Landen|first1=Xander|title=Hallquist isn\u2019t ruling out another run. But for now, she\u2019s job hunting.|url=https://vtdigger.org/2018/11/21/hallquist-isnt-ruling-another-run-now-shes-job-hunting/|publisher=VTDigger|date=November 21, 2018|accessdate=March 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Endorsements===\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Rebecca Holcombe\n| list =\n; Governors\n* [[Madeleine Kunin]], former Governor of Vermont<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sltrib.com/news/politics/2019/05/14/lt-gov-spencer-cox/|title=Lt. Gov. Spencer Cox announces he is running for Utah governor, vows a \u2018different,\u2019 positive campaign|work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=May 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n; State representatives\n* Tim Briglin\n* Kevin \u201cCoach\u201d Christie\n* Sara Coffey\n* Peter Conlon\n* Tim Jerman (former)\n* Martin Lalonde\n* Jim Masland\n* David Potter\n* Ann Pugh\n* Mary Sullivan\n* Maida Townsend\n* David Yacovone\n* Sam Young\n\n;Individuals\n* Dottie Deans, former chair of the Vermont Democratic Party<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rebeccaholcombe.com/supporters/|title=Supporter|website=Rebecca for Vermont|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = David Zuckerman\n| list =\n;Political figures<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zuckermanforvt.com/news/2020/3/11/zuckerman-endorsed-by-democratic-party-leaders|title=Zuckerman Endorsed by Democratic Party Leaders|website=David Zuckerman for Governor|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Faisal Gill]], former chair of the Vermont Democratic Party\n* [[Scudder Parker]], former chair of the Vermont Democratic Party and Vermont state senator\n* Cindy Metcalf, former chair of the Vermont Democratic Party and chief of staff for Lieutenant Governor Racine\n\n;Individuals\n* [[Ben Cohen (businessman)|Ben Cohen]], co-founder of [[Ben & Jerry's]]<ref name=\"ben and jerry\">{{cite web|url=https://www.zuckermanforvt.com/news/2020/2/25/press-release-ben-and-jerry-endorse-david|title=Ben and Jerry Endorse David|website=David Zuckerman for Governor|date=February 23, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Jerry Greenfield]], co-founder of [[Ben & Jerry's]]<ref name=\"ben and jerry\"/>\n* [[Bill McKibben]], environmentalist, scholar at [[Middlebury College]], and leader of [[350.org]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zuckermanforvt.com/news/2020/2/18/press-release-bill-mckibben-endorses-david-zuckerman|title=Bill McKibben Endorses David Zuckerman|website=David Zuckerman for Governor|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Results===\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title = Democratic primary results\n}}\n{{Election box  candidate with party link no change\n|candidate = Rebecca Holcombe\n|party = Vermont Democratic Party\n|votes = \n|percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party = Vermont Democratic Party\n|candidate = Patrick Winburn\n|votes = \n|percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party = Vermont Democratic Party\n|candidate = David Zuckerman\n|votes = \n|percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate = ''Write-ins''\n|party = Vermont Democratic Party\n|votes = \n|percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n|votes = \n|percentage = 100.0%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Progressive primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n* [[David Zuckerman (politician)|David Zuckerman]], [[Lieutenant Governor of Vermont]] (2017\u2013present), member of the [[Vermont Senate]] (2013\u20132017), member of the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] (1997\u20132011), farmer, businessman{{efn|Zuckerman is a member of the [[Vermont Progressive Party]] but also runs in Democratic primaries.}}<ref name=\"ZuckermanRuns\"/>\n====Declined====\n*Brenda Siegel, [[opioid epidemic]] and [[Brattleboro, Vermont|Brattleboro]] [[Hurricane Irene|hurricane relief]] activist, southern Vermont nonprofit founder and executive director, candidate for governor in [[2018 Vermont gubernatorial election|2018]] (running for [[2020 Vermont elections#Lieutenant governor|lieutenant governor]])\n\n===Results===\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title = Progressive primary results\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|party = Vermont Progressive Party\n|candidate = David Zuckerman\n|votes = \n|percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate = ''Write-ins''\n|party = Vermont Progressive Party\n|votes = \n|percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n|votes = \n|percentage = 100.0%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==General election==\n===Predictions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Source\n!Ranking\n!As of\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Sabato's Crystal Ball|Sabato]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://crystalball.centerforpolitics.org/crystalball/2020-governor/|title=2020 Gubernatorial race 