{"title_page": "Antakya", "text_new": "{{about|the capital of Hatay Province}}\n{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|settlement_type               = [[Metropolitan municipalities in Turkey|Metropolitan municipality]]\n|subdivision_type              = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name              = {{TUR}}\n|timezone                      = [[Further-eastern European Time|FET]]\n|utc_offset                    = +3\n|map_caption                   = Location of Antakya within Turkey\n|official_name                 = Antakya\n|image_skyline                 = View of Antakya.jpg\n|image_caption                 = A view of Antakya from high ground\n|subdivision_type1             = [[Regions of Turkey|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1             = [[Mediterranean Region, Turkey|Mediterranean]]\n|subdivision_type2             = [[Provinces of Turkey|Province]]\n|subdivision_name2             = [[Hatay Province]]\n|area_footnotes                = {{Turkey district areas|SOURCE}}\n|area_blank1_title             = District\n|area_blank1_km2               = {{Turkey district areas|Hatay|Antakya}}\n|elevation_m                   = 67\n|population_footnotes          = {{Turkey district populations|SOURCE|Hatay}}\n|population_urban              = {{Turkey district populations|Hatay|Antakya|\u015fehir}}\n|population_as_of              = {{Turkey district populations|YEAR}}\n|population_blank1_title       = District\n|population_blank1             = {{Turkey district populations|Hatay|Antakya|toplam}}\n|population_density_blank1_km2 = auto\n|postal_code_type              = [[Postal code]]\n|postal_code                   = 31xxx\n|blank_info                    = 31\n|blank_name                    = [[Turkish car number plates|Licence&nbsp;plate]]\n|area_code                     = (+90) 326\n|leader_name                   = \n|website                       = {{URL|http://www.antakya.bel.tr}}\n|leader_name1                  = \n|pushpin_map                   = Turkey#Asia Southwest#Europe\n|coordinates                   = {{coord|36|12|N|36|09|E|region:TR|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n'''Antakya''' ({{IPA-tr|\u0251n\u02c8t\u0251kj\u0251}}) is the capital of [[Hatay Province]], the southernmost province of [[Turkey]]. The city is located in a well-watered and fertile valley on the [[Orontes River]], about 20 kilometers (12 mi) from the [[Levantine Sea]].\n\nToday's city stands partly on the site of the ancient '''[[Antioch]]''' ({{lang-grc|\u1f08\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03cc\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1}}, {{transl|grc|Anti\u00f3kheia}}, also known as \"Antioch on the Orontes\"), which was founded in the 4th century BC by the [[Seleucid]]. Antioch later became one of the [[Roman Empire]]'s largest cities, and was made the capital of the provinces of [[Roman Syria|Syria]] and [[Coele-Syria (Roman province)|Coele-Syria]]. It was also an influential early center of [[Christianity]], and gained much ecclesiastical importance in the [[Byzantine Empire]]. Captured by the [[Umar ibn al-Khattab|caliph Umar]] in the 7th century, the medieval '''Antakiyah''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0646\u0637\u0627\u0643\u064a\u0629}}, {{transl|ar|\u02beAn\u1e6d\u0101kiya}}) was conquered or re-conquered several times: by the Byzantine in 969, the [[Seljuk Empire|Seljuk]] in 1084,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fMvQAgAAQBAJ].</ref> the [[Crusades|Crusaders]] in 1098,<ref name=\"Ronald Roberson\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ovotAAAAYAAJ].</ref> the [[Ayyubid]] in 1187, the [[Mamluk]] in 1268,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=R2ZhDgAAQBAJ].</ref> and eventually the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] in 1517,<ref name=\"Ronald Roberson\"/> who would integrate it to the [[Aleppo Eyalet]] then to the [[Aleppo Vilayet]]. The city joined the [[Hatay State]] under the [[French Mandate]] before joining the [[Turkish Republic]].\n\nMost of the population, which was approximately 216,960 as of 2012, speaks Turkish as their native language, while a minority are native Arabic speakers.\n\n==History==\n\n===Antiquity===\n{{Main|Antioch}}\nThe area of Antioch has been occupied by humans since the [[Calcolithic]] era (6th millennium BC), as revealed by [[archeological]] excavations of the mound of [[Tell Atchana|Tell-A\u00e7ana]], among others.{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\nThe King of Macedon [[Alexander the Great]], after defeating the [[Persian Empire|Persians]] in the [[Battle of Issus]] in 333 BC, followed the [[Orontes river|Orontes]] south into Syria and occupied the area. The city of Antioch was founded in 300 BC, after the death of Alexander, by the Hellenistic [[Seleucid]] King [[Seleucus I Nicator]].{{fact|date=January 2019}} It played an important role as one of the largest cities in the Hellenistic Seleucid Kingdom, in the [[Roman Empire]], and in the [[Byzantine Empire]]. It was a key city during the early [[history of Christianity]], in particular that of the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] and the [[Antiochian Orthodox Church]], as well as during the [[rise of Islam]] and [[the Crusades]].\n\n===Rashidun period===\n[[File:Fall of Antioch in 969.png|thumb|Recapture of Antioch in 969]]\n\nIn 637, during the reign of the Byzantine emperor [[Heraclius]], Antioch was conquered by the [[Rashidun Caliphate]] during the [[Battle of the Iron Bridge]]. The city became known in Arabic as {{lang|ar|\u0623\u0646\u0637\u0627\u0643\u064a\u0629}} ({{transl|ar|\u02beAn\u1e6d\u0101kiya}}). Since the [[Umayyad|Umayyad dynasty]] was unable to penetrate the [[Anatolia]]n plateau, Antioch found itself on the frontline of the conflicts between two hostile empires during the next 350&nbsp;years, so that the city went into a precipitous decline.\n\nIn 969, the city was reconquered for the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] Emperor [[Nikephoros II Phokas]] by [[Michael Bourtzes]] and the ''[[stratopedarches]]'' [[Peter (stratopedarches)|Peter]]. It soon became the seat of a ''[[dux]]'', who commanded the forces of the local [[Theme (Byzantine district)|themes]] and was the most important officer on the Empire's eastern border,{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} held by such men as [[Nikephoros Ouranos]]. In 1078, [[Philaretos Brachamios]], an Armenian rebel, seized power. He held the city until the [[Seljuk Turks]] captured it from him in 1084. The [[Sultanate of Rum]] held it only fourteen years before the Crusaders arrived.{{sfn|Rockwell|1911|p=131}}\n\n===Crusader era===\n[[File:Capture of Antioch by Bohemond of Tarente in June 1098.JPG|left|thumb|[[Capture of Antioch]] by [[Louis Gallait]]]]\n{{Main|Principality of Antioch}}\nThe Crusaders' [[Siege of Antioch]] during the [[First Crusade]] resulted in its fall. The Crusaders caused significant damage, including a three-day massacre of its population, both Christian and Muslim. Following the defeat of the Turkish garrison, [[Bohemond I of Antioch|Bohemond I]] became its overlord. It remained the capital of the Latin [[Principality of Antioch]] for nearly two centuries.\n\nIn 1268 it fell to the Egyptian [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk]] Sultan [[Baibars]] after [[Siege of Antioch (1268)|another siege]]. Baibars proceeded to massacre the Christian population.<ref>[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Asia/Armenia/_Texts/KURARM/30*.html Vahan M. Kurkjian, \"New Scourge from Egypt\", in ''A History of Armenia'']</ref> In addition to suffering the ravages of war, the city lost its commercial importance because trade routes to [[East Asia]] moved north following the 13th-century [[Mongol]] conquests. Antioch never recovered as a major city, with much of its former role falling to the port city of [[Alexandretta]] (''\u0130skenderun''). An account of both cities as they were in 1675 appears in the diary of the English naval chaplain [[Henry Teonge]].\n\n===Ottoman city===\n{{Expand section|date=July 2015}}\n[[File:AntiochMap1912.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Densely built Antakya in 1912: the traditional Muslim city shows no trace of its Hellenistic planning. To the east, orchards (green) fill the plain.]]\nThe city was the center of the [[Sanjak]] of Antakya, part of the [[Damascus Eyalet]].\n\nIn 1822 (and again in 1872), Antakya was hit by an earthquake and damaged.  When Ottoman general [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]] established his headquarters in the city in 1835, it had only some 5,000 inhabitants.  Supporters hoped the city might develop thanks to the [[Euphrates]] Valley [[Railway]], which was supposed to link it to the port of Sueida (now ''[[Samanda\u011f\u0131 (city)|Samanda\u011f\u0131]]''). However, such plans were doomed to come to naught. This scheme is the subject of [[Letitia Elizabeth Landon]]'s poem {{ws|[[s:Letitia Elizabeth Landon (L. E. L.) in Fisher's Drawing Room Scrap Book, 1837/Antioch|Antioch]]}} (1836) in which she reflects of the superiority of trade and commerce over war and conflict. The city suffered repeated outbreaks of [[cholera]] due to inadequate infrastructure for sanitation.{{sfn|Rockwell|1911|p=131}}  Later the city developed and rapidly resumed much of its old importance when a railway was built along the lower Orontes Valley.\n\n===Republic of Hatay and modern Turkey===\nSee [[Hatay Province]] for the history of the region during the demise of the [[Ottoman Empire]], the short-lived [[Republic of Hatay]] (in 1938), and the area's incorporation into the Republic of Turkey in 1939.\n\n==Demographics in 1935==\nIn 1935, Turkish and Arab Muslims made more than 80% of population.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Census of 1935<ref name=dump>{{cite book|last=Dumper|first=Michael|title=Cities of the Middle East and North Africa: A Historical Encyclopedia|date=2007|publisher=ABC-CLIO|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3SapTk5iGDkC&pg=PA40|page=40}}</ref><ref name=julian>{{cite book|last=Go|first=Julian|title=Decentering Social Theory|date=2013|publisher=Emerald Group Publishing|isbn=9781781907276|page=31|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ReJbAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA31&dq=1935+census}}</ref> \n|- \n! Ethnic group\n! Population (percentage)\n|-\n| Sunni [[Muslim]]s || 19,720 (58%)<ref name=julian />\n|-\n| Alawites || 8,670  (25.5%)<ref name=julian />\n|-\n| Christians || 4,930 (14.5%)<ref name=julian />\n|-\n| Others || 680 (2%) \n|-\n| Total\u00b9 || 34,000 (100%)<ref name=julian />\n|-\n|}\n\u00b9Most Alawis and Armenians spoke Turkish as a second language<ref name=dump /> and spoke either Arabic or Armenian as a first language.\n\nA British traveller at Antakya in year 1798 said \"the language here is generally Turkish\" (while, by contrast the prevalent language at [[Aleppo]] at the time was Arabic).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1nshAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA449 ''Travels in Africa, Egypt, and Syria, from the Year 1792 to 1798''], by William George Browne, year 1806 on page 449 (and page 442 for Aleppo).</ref>\n\n==City of Antakya today==\n[[File:AntakyaCarsi.JPG|thumb|The market place in central Antakya]]\n[[File:Roman Catholic Church Antakya 1.jpg|thumb|Courtyard of the Church of Apostles Peter and Paul in Antakya]]\n\nMount Habib-i Neccar (Habib An-Najar in Sura al Yassin 36:13 ) and the city walls which climb the hillsides symbolise Antakya, making the city a formidable fortress built on a series of hills running north-east to south-west. Antakya was originally centred on the east bank of the river.  Since the 19th century, the city has expanded with new neighbourhoods built on the plains across the river to the south-west, and four bridges connect the old and new cities. Many of the buildings of the last two decades are styled as concrete blocks, and Antakya has lost much of its classic beauty.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} The narrow streets of the old city can become clogged with traffic.\n\nAlthough the port city [[Iskenderun]] has become the largest city in Hatay, Antakya is a provincial capital still of considerable importance as the centre of a large district.  The draining of [[Lake Amik]] and development of land has caused the region's economy to grow in wealth and productivity. The town is a lively shopping and business centre with many restaurants, cinemas and other amenities. This district is centred on a large park opposite the governor's building and the central avenue ''Kurtulu\u015f Caddes\u0131''. The tea gardens, cafes and restaurants in the neighbourhood of ''[[Harbiye, Antakya|Harbiye]]'' are popular destinations, particularly for the variety of ''[[meze]]'' in the restaurants. The [[Orontes river|Orontes]] River can be malodorous when water is low in summer. Rather than formal nightlife, in the summer heat, people will stay outside until late in the night to walk with their families and friends, and munch on snacks.\n\nIts location near the Syrian border makes Antakya more cosmopolitan than many cities in Turkey. It did not attract the mass immigration of people from eastern Anatolia in the 1980s and 1990s that radically swelled the populations of Mediterranean cities such as [[Adana]] and [[Mersin]]. Both [[Turkish language|Turkish]] and [[Arabic]] are still widely spoken in Antakya, although written Arabic is rarely used. A mixed community of faiths and denominations co-exist peacefully here.  Although almost all the inhabitants are [[Muslim]], a substantial proportion adhere to the [[Alevi]] and the Arab Alawi traditions, in 'Harbiye' there is a place to honour the saint [[Khidr|H\u0131z\u0131r]]. Numerous tombs of saints, of both [[Sunni]] and [[Alawite]], are located throughout the city.  Several small Christian communities are active in the city, with the largest church being St. Peter and St. Paul on Hurriyet Caddesi. With its long history of spiritual and religious movements, Antakya is a place of pilgrimage for Christians. The Jewish community of Antakya had shrunk to 14 members in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chudacoff|first1=Danya|title=Turkey's Jewish community longs for the past|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/04/turkey-jewish-community-antakya-20144227111824684.html|website=Aljazeera|accessdate=February 18, 2018|date=May 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>Avotaynu: the international review of Jewish genealogy, Volume 14, G. Mokotoff, 1998, [https://books.google.com/books?id=77RtAAAAMAAJ&q=Information+comes+from+the+Jewish+communities+of+Antakya+Bodrum+Bursa+Canakkale+Corlu+Edirne+Finike+Gelibolu+Iskendorun+Istanbul+Izmir+Kilis+Kirklarelli+Manisa+and+Tire+plus+a+few+scattered+stones+from+other+Gazi-Antep&dq=Information+comes+from+the+Jewish+communities+of+Antakya+Bodrum+Bursa+Canakkale+Corlu+Edirne+Finike+Gelibolu+Iskendorun+Istanbul+Izmir+Kilis+Kirklarelli+Manisa+and+Tire+plus+a+few+scattered+stones+from+other+Gazi-Antep&hl=en&ei=fbSJTo7lNe7zmAWQyegX&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAA p. 40.]</ref> It has a reputation in Turkey as a place for spells, fortune telling, miracles and spirits.\n\nLocal crafts include a soap scented with the oil of [[bay Laurel|bay tree]].\n\n==Geography==\nAntakya is located on the banks of the [[Orontes River]] ({{lang-tr|Asi Nehri}}), approximately {{convert|22|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} inland from the [[Mediterranean]] coast. The city is in a valley surrounded by mountains, the [[Nur Mountains]] (ancient Amanos) to the north and Mount Kelda\u011f (Jebel Akra) to the south, with the 440 m high Mount Habib-i Neccar (the ancient Mount Silpius) forming its eastern limits. The mountains are a source of a green [[marble]]. Antakya is at the northern edge of the [[Dead Sea Rift]] and vulnerable to earthquakes.\n\nThe plain of [[Amik]] to the north-east of the city is fertile soil watered by the Orontes, the [[Karasu (Hatay)|Karasu]] and the [[Afrin River|Afrin]] rivers; the lake in the plain was drained in 1980 by a French company. At the same time channels were built to widen the Orontes and let it pass neatly through the city centre. The Orontes is joined in Antakya by the Hac\u0131 K\u00fcr\u00fc\u015f stream to the north-east of the city near the church of St Peter, and the Ham\u015fen which runs down from Habib-i Neccar to the south-west, under Memekli Bridge near the army barracks. Flora includes the [[bay Laurel|bay tree]]s and [[Myrtle (plant)|myrtle]].\n\n===Climate===\n\nThe city enjoys a [[hot-summer Mediterranean climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Csa'') with hot and dry summers, and mild and wet winters; however due to its higher altitude, Antakya has slightly cooler temperatures than the coast.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Antakya\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high F = 51\n|Feb high F = 57\n|Mar high F = 64\n|Apr high F = 71\n|May high F = 78\n|Jun high F = 82\n|Jul high F = 86\n|Aug high F = 87\n|Sep high F = 86\n|Oct high F = 80\n|Nov high F = 68\n|Dec high F = 55\n|year high F = 71\n|Jan low F = 39\n|Feb low F = 41\n|Mar low F = 46\n|Apr low F = 51\n|May low F = 59\n|Jun low F = 68\n|Jul low F = 73\n|Aug low F = 75\n|Sep low F = 68\n|Oct low F = 57\n|Nov low F = 46\n|Dec low F = 41\n|year low F = 55\n|Jan precipitation inch = 7.5\n|Feb precipitation inch = 6.5\n|Mar precipitation inch = 5.6\n|Apr precipitation inch = 4.2\n|May precipitation inch = 3.2\n|Jun precipitation inch = 1.3\n|Jul precipitation inch = 0.3\n|Aug precipitation inch = 0.2\n|Sep precipitation inch = 1.1\n|Oct precipitation inch = 3.5\n|Nov precipitation inch = 4.3\n|Dec precipitation inch = 7.5\n|year precipitation inch = 45.1\n|source 1 = Weatherbase<ref name=Weatherbase>{{cite web\n| url =http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=173702&refer=&units=us |title =Weatherbase: Weather for Antakya, Turkey | publisher=Weatherbase | year=2011 }} Retrieved on November 22, 2011.</ref>\n|date=November 2011\n}}\n\n==Education==\n[[Mustafa Kemal University]], abbreviated as MKU, has several faculties including Engineering and Medicine, while having a campus called Tayfur S\u00f6kmen located in Serinyol district {{convert|15|km|mi|abbr=on}}, north of Antakya (centrum).\nEstablished in 1992, currently more than 32,000 students enrolled at the university.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mku.edu.tr/main.php?page=readpage&id=980&location=oidb |publisher=MKU |title=About Mustafa Kemal University (MKU) |accessdate=2011-03-26 }}</ref>\n\nBesides the campus in Serinyol, MKU has its faculties spread out in all main districts of the province including Alt\u0131n\u00f6z\u00fc, Antakya, Belen, D\u00f6rtyol, Erzin, Hassa, \u0130skenderun, K\u0131r\u0131khan, Reyhanl\u0131, Samanda\u011f and Yaylada\u011f\u0131.\n\n==Main sights==\nThe long and varied history has created many architectural sites of interest. There is much for visitors to see in Antakya, although many buildings have been lost in the rapid growth and redevelopment of the city in recent decades.\n* [[Hatay Archaeology Museum]] has the second largest collection of [[Roman Empire|Roman]] [[mosaics]] in the world.\n* The rock-carved ''[[Church of St Peter]]'', with its network of refuges and tunnels carved out of the rock, a site of Christian pilgrimage. There are also tombs cut into the rock face at various places along the Orontes valley.\n*Old market district: It offers plenty of traditional shops, where you can explore what you have not seen before. It is exactly in the city centre, you are in when you see the sign ''Uzun \u00c7ar\u015f\u0131 Caddesi''.\n* The seedy ''G\u00fcnd\u00fcz cinema'' in the city centre was once used as parliament building of the [[Republic of Hatay]].\n* The waterfalls at the [[Harbiye, Antakya|Harbiye]] / Daphne promenade.\n* The [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] ''Habib-i Neccar Camii'', the oldest mosque in Antakya and one of the oldest in [[Anatolia]].\n* The labyrinth of narrow streets and old Antakya houses. This district is the oldtown in fact.\n* [[Vespasianus Titus Tunnel]]-Samandag\u0131. It is approximately 35&nbsp;km. far from the centre.\n* Be\u015fikli Cave and Graves (the antique city of Seleukeia Pierria)\n* St. Simon Monastery\n* [[Bagras|Bagras (Bakras) Castle]], which was built in antiquity and restored many times in later centuries (particularly during the [[Crusades]], when it was a stronghold of the [[Knights Templar]]), served as a watchtower on the {{convert|27|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} mountain road from [[\u0130skenderun]] (Alexandretta) to Antakya (Antioch).\n* The panoramic view of the city from the heights of Mount Habib-i Neccar\n[[File:ANTAKYA EYL\u00dcL 2011 - panoramio (1).jpg|thumb|St. Paul Orthodox Church.]]\n* St. Paul Orthodox Church\n\nWith its rich architectural heritage, Antakya is a member of the [[Norwich]]-based [[European Association of Historic Towns and Regions]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20090917224421/http://www.historic-towns.org/documents/members/turkey.doc]. The Roman bridge (thought to date from the era of [[Diocletian]]) was destroyed in 1972 during the widening and channelling of the [[Orontes River|Orontes]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}\n\n{{wide image|Antioch Panorama Saint Pierre Church.jpg|900px|align-cap=center|A panoramic view of Antakya from the Church of Saint Peter}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Antakya view 1.jpg|Antakya view\nFile:Antakya view 3.jpg|Antakya view\nFile:Antakya view 6156.jpg|Antakya view\nFile:Antakya Yeni Camii 6216.jpg|Antakya Yeni Camii Exterior\nFile:Antakya Yeni Camii 7350.jpg|Antakya Yeni Camii Interior\nFile:Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii 088.jpg|Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii Interior\nFile:Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii 5859.jpg|Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii Exterior\nFile:Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii 7786.jpg|Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii Exterior\nFile:Antakya Mahremiye camii 2357.jpg|Antakya Mahremiye camii Minaret and top gate\nFile:Antakya Mahremiye camii 2358.jpg|Antakya Mahremiye camii Interior\nFile:Antakya Mahremiye camii 7377.jpg|Antakya Mahremiye camii Minaret and gate\nFile:Antakya Sarimiye Mosque 2711.jpg|Antakya Sarimiye Mosque Minaret\nFile:Antakya Ulu Cami 6228.jpg|Antakya Ulu Cami Entrance to courtyard\nFile:Antakya Ulu Cami 7312.jpg|Antakya Ulu Cami\nFile:Antakya Ulu Cami 7316.jpg|Antakya Ulu Cami\nFile:Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas, Antakya (Antioch).jpg|View of the river in the 1780s, by [[Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas]].\nFile:Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas, Antioche, appeler par les Arabes Anthakyeh, Vue de la pote Bab El Medynah.jpg|Medina gate in the 1780s, by [[Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas]].\n\nFile:Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas, Antioche, appeler par les Arabes Anthakyeh.jpg|Ruins of the Seleucus palace in the 1780s, by [[Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas]].\n\n\n\n\n</gallery>\n\n== Transport ==\nThe city is served from [[Hatay Airport]].\n\n==Sports==\nAntakya has one male professional [[Association football|football]] club, [[Hatayspor]], who play in the [[TFF First League|TFF 1. Lig]]. There is also a female professional team called [[Hatay B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyesi (women's football)|Hatay B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyesi]]. [[Hatay B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyespor (women's basketball)|Hatay B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyespor]], a woman's basketball team, is also present, and plays in the [[Turkish Women's Basketball League]].\n\n==Cuisine==\nThe cuisine of Antakya is renowned. Its cuisine is considered [[Levantine cuisine|levantine]] rather than [[Turkish cuisine|Turkish]]. The cuisine offers plenty of meals, where beef and lambs are mainly used. Popular dishes include the typical Turkish ''[[kebab]]'', served with spices and onions in flat unleavened bread, with yoghurt as ''ali nazik'' kebab, oruk, kaytaz b\u00f6re\u011fi and kat\u0131kl\u0131 ekmek . Hot spicy food is a feature of this part of Turkey, along with [[Turkish coffee]] and local specialities. Here are some savour:\n\n* ''\u0130\u00e7li k\u00f6fte'' and other [[oruk]] varieties: varieties of the Arabic ''[[kibbeh]]'', deep-fried balls of [[bulgur]] wheat stuffed with minced meat; or baked in ovens in cylinder-cone shape. Sa\u00e7 oru\u011fu is made of the same ingredients, however in circular shape. \n*''Kaytaz b\u00f6re\u011fi'': It is patty that is made of wheat, beef, tomato and onion.\n*''Kat\u0131kl\u0131 ekmek'': Ingredients in Kat\u0131kl\u0131 Ekmek usually consist of wheat, traditional pepper (paste), spices such as sesame and theme, \u00e7\u00f6kelek or cheese. It looks like an ancestor of pizza. Not a lot of restaurants serve it, however it can be found in old-market that is located in the centre and Harbiye.\n* [[Pomegranate]] syrup, used as a salad dressing, called ''debes ramman'', a traditional [[Levantine cuisine|Levantine Arabic]] dressing.\n* ''Semirsek'', a thin bread with hot [[Capsicum|pepper]], minced meat or spinach filling\n* Spicy chicken, a specialty of Harbiye\n* [[Za'atar]] (Zahter) a traditional [[Levantine Arabic]] paste of spiced thyme, oregano, and sesame seeds, mixed with olive oil, spread on flat (called ''pide'' or in English pita) bread.\n* Fresh [[chick peas]], munched as a snack.\n* ''[[Harees|Hirise]]'', boiled and pounded wheat meal.\n* ''A\u015fur'', meat mixed with crushed wheat, chickpea, cumin, onion, pepper and walnut\n\n;''[[Meze]]''\n* [[Hummus]] - the chick-pea dip\n* pureed [[fava beans]]\n* [[Patl\u0131can salatas\u0131]]: Patl\u0131can salatas\u0131 or babaganoush, made of baked and sliced aubergines that mixed\nwith pepper and tomato. It is usually served with pomegranate syrup.\n* [[Taratur]]: Known also as Tarator, made of walnuts, 'tahin', yogurt and garlic. \n* ''S\u00fczme yo\u011furt'': A type of yogurt that its water content is removed with traditional methods.\n* ''Ezme biber'': It is made of pepper and walnuts.\n* [[Surke]] - dried [[curds]] served in spicy olive oil\n* ''\u00c7\u00f6kelek'' - the spicy sun-dried cheese\n* [[Eel]]s from the Orontes, spiced and fried in [[olive oil]]\n\n;Sweets/desserts\n* ''[[Kanafeh|K\u00fcnefe]]'' - a hot cheese, ''kadaif''-based sweet. Antakya is Turkey's ''k\u00fcnefe'' capital; the pastry shops in the centre compete to claim being kings {{lang-tr|kral}} of the pastry.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* ''M\u00fc\u015febbek'' - rings of deep fried pastry.\n* ''Peynirli irmik helvas\u0131'' - Peynirli \u0130rmik Helvas\u0131 is a dessert that is made of semolina, sugar and traditional cheese that is the same as used in k\u00fcnefe. It is served warm, especially in restaurants in the region Harbiye, rather than k\u00fcnefe shops that are located in the centre.\n\n== Twin towns ==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Turkey}}\n\nAntakya is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Aalen]], [[Germany]] (since 1995).\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Alexandros of Antioch|Alexandros]] (1st century BC) Greek sculptor\n*[[George of Antioch]]\n*[[Ignatius of Antioch]], Patriarch of Antioch\n*[[John Chrysostom]] (349\u2013407) Patriarch of Constantinople\n* [[Saint Luke]], 1st century AD, Christian evangelist and author of the [[Gospel of St. Luke]] and [[Acts of the Apostles]]\n*[[Ya\u011f\u0131s\u0131yan]], [[Seljukid]] governor of the city up to its capture by the Crusaders \n* [[Sel\u00e2hattin \u00dclk\u00fcmen]] - [[Righteous among the nations]]\n*[[Tayfur S\u00f6kmen]] - The president of the [[Republic of Hatay]] during its existence between the years 1938 and 1939.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{Cite book|title = Ancient Antioch |author=Glanville Downey|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|year=1963}}\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Antioch|volume=2|pages=130-132|first=William Walker|last=Rockwell|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikivoyage|Antakya}}\n* [http://www.pbase.com/dosseman/Antakya Pictures of Antakya]\n* [http://www.pbase.com/dosseman/antakya_museum Pictures of Antakya Museum]\n\n{{Districts of Turkey|provname=Hatay|image=Hatay|sortkey=Antakya}}\n{{Characters and names in the Quran}}\n{{Metropolitan municipalities in Turkey}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Antakya|*]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Hatay Province]]\n[[Category:\u00c7ukurova]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Hatay Province]]\n[[Category:Populated places along the Silk Road]]\n[[Category:Crusade places]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek archaeological sites in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Seleucid colonies in Anatolia]]\n[[Category:Holy cities]]\n[[Category:New Testament places]]\n[[Category:Roman sites in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 4th century BC]]\n[[Category:Jewish communities in Turkey]]\n[[Category:300s BC establishments]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the capital of Hatay Province}}\n{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|settlement_type               = [[Metropolitan municipalities in Turkey|Metropolitan municipality]]\n|subdivision_type              = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name              = {{TUR}}\n|timezone                      = [[Further-eastern European Time|FET]]\n|utc_offset                    = +3\n|map_caption                   = Location of Antakya within Turkey\n|official_name                 = Antakya\n|image_skyline                 = View of Antakya.jpg\n|image_caption                 = A view of Antakya from high ground\n|subdivision_type1             = [[Regions of Turkey|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1             = [[Mediterranean Region, Turkey|Mediterranean]]\n|subdivision_type2             = [[Provinces of Turkey|Province]]\n|subdivision_name2             = [[Hatay Province]]\n|area_footnotes                = {{Turkey district areas|SOURCE}}\n|area_blank1_title             = District\n|area_blank1_km2               = {{Turkey district areas|Hatay|Antakya}}\n|elevation_m                   = 67\n|population_footnotes          = {{Turkey district populations|SOURCE|Hatay}}\n|population_urban              = {{Turkey district populations|Hatay|Antakya|\u015fehir}}\n|population_as_of              = {{Turkey district populations|YEAR}}\n|population_blank1_title       = District\n|population_blank1             = {{Turkey district populations|Hatay|Antakya|toplam}}\n|population_density_blank1_km2 = auto\n|postal_code_type              = [[Postal code]]\n|postal_code                   = 31xxx\n|blank_info                    = 31\n|blank_name                    = [[Turkish car number plates|Licence&nbsp;plate]]\n|area_code                     = (+90) 326\n|leader_name                   = \n|website                       = {{URL|http://www.antakya.bel.tr}}\n|leader_name1                  = \n|pushpin_map                   = Turkey#Asia Southwest#Europe\n|coordinates                   = {{coord|36|12|N|36|09|E|region:TR|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n'''Antakya''' ({{IPA-tr|\u0251n\u02c8t\u0251kj\u0251}}) is the capital of [[Hatay Province]], the southernmost province of [[Turkey]]. The city is located in a well-watered and fertile valley on the [[Orontes River]], about 20 kilometers (12 mi) from the [[Levantine Sea]].\n\nToday's city stands partly on the site of the ancient '''[[Antioch]]''' ({{lang-grc|\u1f08\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03cc\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1}}, {{transl|grc|Anti\u00f3kheia}}, also known as \"Antioch on the Orontes\"), which was founded in the 4th century BC by the [[Seleucid]]. Antioch later became one of the [[Roman Empire]]'s largest cities, and was made the capital of the provinces of [[Roman Syria|Syria]] and [[Coele-Syria (Roman province)|Coele-Syria]]. It was also an influential early center of [[Christianity]], and gained much ecclesiastical importance in the [[Byzantine Empire]]. Captured by the [[Umar ibn al-Khattab|caliph Umar]] in the 7th century, the medieval '''Antakiyah''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0646\u0637\u0627\u0643\u064a\u0629}}, {{transl|ar|\u02beAn\u1e6d\u0101kiya}}) was conquered or re-conquered several times: by the Byzantine in 969, the [[Seljuk Empire|Seljuk]] in 1084,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fMvQAgAAQBAJ].</ref> the [[Crusades|Crusaders]] in 1098,<ref name=\"Ronald Roberson\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ovotAAAAYAAJ].</ref> the [[Ayyubid]] in 1187, the [[Mamluk]] in 1268,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=R2ZhDgAAQBAJ].</ref> and eventually the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] in 1517,<ref name=\"Ronald Roberson\"/> who would integrate it to the [[Aleppo Eyalet]] then to the [[Aleppo Vilayet]]. The city joined the [[Hatay State]] under the [[French Mandate]] before joining the [[Turkish Republic]].\n\nMost of the population, which was approximately 216,960 as of 2012, speaks Turkish as their native language, while a minority are native Arabic speakers.\n\n==History==\n\n===Antiquity===\n{{Main|Antioch}}\nThe area of Antioch has been occupied by humans since the [[Calcolithic]] era (6th millennium BC), as revealed by [[archeological]] excavations of the mound of [[Tell Atchana|Tell-A\u00e7ana]], among others.{{fact|date=January 2019}}\n\nThe King of Macedon [[Alexander the Great]], after defeating the [[Persian Empire|Persians]] in the [[Battle of Issus]] in 333 BC, followed the [[Orontes river|Orontes]] south into Syria and occupied the area. The city of Antioch was founded in 300 BC, after the death of Alexander, by the Hellenistic [[Seleucid]] King [[Seleucus I Nicator]].{{fact|date=January 2019}} It played an important role as one of the largest cities in the Hellenistic Seleucid Kingdom, in the [[Roman Empire]], and in the [[Byzantine Empire]]. It was a key city during the early [[history of Christianity]], in particular that of the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]] and the [[Antiochian Orthodox Church]], as well as during the [[rise of Islam]] and [[the Crusades]].\n\n===Rashidun period===\n[[File:Fall of Antioch in 969.png|thumb|Recapture of Antioch in 969]]\n\nIn 637, during the reign of the Byzantine emperor [[Heraclius]], Antioch was conquered by the [[Rashidun Caliphate]] during the [[Battle of the Iron Bridge]]. The city became known in Arabic as {{lang|ar|\u0623\u0646\u0637\u0627\u0643\u064a\u0629}} ({{transl|ar|\u02beAn\u1e6d\u0101kiya}}). Since the [[Umayyad|Umayyad dynasty]] was unable to penetrate the [[Anatolia]]n plateau, Antioch found itself on the frontline of the conflicts between two hostile empires during the next 350&nbsp;years, so that the city went into a precipitous decline.\n\nIn 969, the city was reconquered for the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] Emperor [[Nikephoros II Phokas]] by [[Michael Bourtzes]] and the ''[[stratopedarches]]'' [[Peter (stratopedarches)|Peter]]. It soon became the seat of a ''[[dux]]'', who commanded the forces of the local [[Theme (Byzantine district)|themes]] and was the most important officer on the Empire's eastern border,{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}} held by such men as [[Nikephoros Ouranos]]. In 1078, [[Philaretos Brachamios]], an Armenian rebel, seized power. He held the city until the [[Seljuk Turks]] captured it from him in 1084. The [[Sultanate of Rum]] held it only fourteen years before the Crusaders arrived.{{sfn|Rockwell|1911|p=131}}\n\n===Crusader era===\n[[File:Capture of Antioch by Bohemond of Tarente in June 1098.JPG|left|thumb|[[Capture of Antioch]] by [[Louis Gallait]]]]\n{{Main|Principality of Antioch}}\nThe Crusaders' [[Siege of Antioch]] during the [[First Crusade]] resulted in its fall. The Crusaders caused significant damage, including a 3-day massacre of its population both Christian and Muslim. Following the defeat of the Turkish garrison, [[Bohemond I of Antioch|Bohemond I]] became its overlord. It remained the capital of the Latin [[Principality of Antioch]] for nearly two centuries.\n\nIn 1268 it fell to the Egyptian [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk]] Sultan [[Baibars]] after [[Siege of Antioch (1268)|another siege]]. Baibars proceeded to massacre the Christian population.<ref>[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Asia/Armenia/_Texts/KURARM/30*.html Vahan M. Kurkjian, \"New Scourge from Egypt\", in ''A History of Armenia'']</ref> In addition to suffering the ravages of war, the city lost its commercial importance because trade routes to the [[Far East]] moved north following the 13th-century [[Mongol]] conquests. Antioch never recovered as a major city, with much of its former role falling to the port city of [[Alexandretta]] (''\u0130skenderun''). An account of both cities as they were in 1675 appears in the diary of the English naval chaplain [[Henry Teonge]].\n\n===Ottoman city===\n{{Expand section|date=July 2015}}\n[[File:AntiochMap1912.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Densely built Antakya in 1912: the traditional Muslim city shows no trace of its Hellenistic planning. To the east, orchards (green) fill the plain.]]\nThe city was the center of the [[Sanjak]] of Antakya, part of the [[Damascus Eyalet]].\n\nIn 1822 (and again in 1872), Antakya was hit by an earthquake and damaged.  When Ottoman general [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]] established his headquarters in the city in 1835, it had only some 5,000 inhabitants.  Supporters hoped the city might develop thanks to the [[Euphrates]] Valley [[Railway]], which was supposed to link it to the port of Sueida (now ''[[Samanda\u011f\u0131 (city)|Samanda\u011f\u0131]]''). However, such plans were doomed to come to naught. This scheme is the subject of [[Letitia Elizabeth Landon]]'s poem {{ws|[[s:Letitia Elizabeth Landon (L. E. L.) in Fisher's Drawing Room Scrap Book, 1837/Antioch|Antioch]]}} (1836) in which she reflects of the superiority of trade and commerce over war and conflict. The city suffered repeated outbreaks of [[cholera]] due to inadequate infrastructure for sanitation.{{sfn|Rockwell|1911|p=131}}  Later the city developed and rapidly resumed much of its old importance when a railway was built along the lower Orontes Valley.\n\n===Republic of Hatay and modern Turkey===\nSee [[Hatay Province]] for the history of the region during the demise of the [[Ottoman Empire]], the short-lived [[Republic of Hatay]] (in 1938), and the area's incorporation into the Republic of Turkey in 1939.\n\n==Demographics in 1935==\nIn 1935, Turkish and Arab Muslims made more than 80% of population.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Census of 1935<ref name=dump>{{cite book|last=Dumper|first=Michael|title=Cities of the Middle East and North Africa: A Historical Encyclopedia|date=2007|publisher=ABC-CLIO|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3SapTk5iGDkC&pg=PA40|page=40}}</ref><ref name=julian>{{cite book|last=Go|first=Julian|title=Decentering Social Theory|date=2013|publisher=Emerald Group Publishing|isbn=9781781907276|page=31|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ReJbAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA31&dq=1935+census}}</ref> \n|- \n! Ethnic group\n! Population (percentage)\n|-\n| Sunni [[Muslim]]s || 19,720 (58%)<ref name=julian />\n|-\n| Alawites || 8,670  (25.5%)<ref name=julian />\n|-\n| Christians || 4,930 (14.5%)<ref name=julian />\n|-\n| Others || 680 (2%) \n|-\n| Total\u00b9 || 34,000 (100%)<ref name=julian />\n|-\n|}\n\u00b9Most Alawis and Armenians spoke Turkish as a second language<ref name=dump /> and spoke either Arabic or Armenian as a first language.\n\nA British traveller at Antakya in year 1798 said \"the language here is generally Turkish\" (while, by contrast the prevalent language at [[Aleppo]] at the time was Arabic).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1nshAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA449 ''Travels in Africa, Egypt, and Syria, from the Year 1792 to 1798''], by William George Browne, year 1806 on page 449 (and page 442 for Aleppo).</ref>\n\n==City of Antakya today==\n[[File:AntakyaCarsi.JPG|thumb|The market place in central Antakya]]\n[[File:Roman Catholic Church Antakya 1.jpg|thumb|Courtyard of the Church of Apostles Peter and Paul in Antakya]]\n\nMount Habib-i Neccar (Habib An-Najar in Sura al Yassin 36:13 ) and the city walls which climb the hillsides symbolise Antakya, making the city a formidable fortress built on a series of hills running north-east to south-west. Antakya was originally centred on the east bank of the river.  Since the 19th century, the city has expanded with new neighbourhoods built on the plains across the river to the south-west, and four bridges connect the old and new cities. Many of the buildings of the last two decades are styled as concrete blocks, and Antakya has lost much of its classic beauty.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} The narrow streets of the old city can become clogged with traffic.\n\nAlthough the port city [[Iskenderun]] has become the largest city in Hatay, Antakya is a provincial capital still of considerable importance as the centre of a large district.  The draining of [[Lake Amik]] and development of land has caused the region's economy to grow in wealth and productivity. The town is a lively shopping and business centre with many restaurants, cinemas and other amenities. This district is centred on a large park opposite the governor's building and the central avenue ''Kurtulu\u015f Caddes\u0131''. The tea gardens, cafes and restaurants in the neighbourhood of ''[[Harbiye, Antakya|Harbiye]]'' are popular destinations, particularly for the variety of ''[[meze]]'' in the restaurants. The [[Orontes river|Orontes]] River can be malodorous when water is low in summer. Rather than formal nightlife, in the summer heat, people will stay outside until late in the night to walk with their families and friends, and munch on snacks.\n\nIts location near the Syrian border makes Antakya more cosmopolitan than many cities in Turkey. It did not attract the mass immigration of people from eastern Anatolia in the 1980s and 1990s that radically swelled the populations of Mediterranean cities such as [[Adana]] and [[Mersin]]. Both [[Turkish language|Turkish]] and [[Arabic]] are still widely spoken in Antakya, although written Arabic is rarely used. A mixed community of faiths and denominations co-exist peacefully here.  Although almost all the inhabitants are [[Muslim]], a substantial proportion adhere to the [[Alevi]] and the Arab Alawi traditions, in 'Harbiye' there is a place to honour the saint [[Khidr|H\u0131z\u0131r]]. Numerous tombs of saints, of both [[Sunni]] and [[Alawite]], are located throughout the city.  Several small Christian communities are active in the city, with the largest church being St. Peter and St. Paul on Hurriyet Caddesi. With its long history of spiritual and religious movements, Antakya is a place of pilgrimage for Christians. The Jewish community of Antakya had shrunk to 14 members in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chudacoff|first1=Danya|title=Turkey's Jewish community longs for the past|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/04/turkey-jewish-community-antakya-20144227111824684.html|website=Aljazeera|accessdate=February 18, 2018|date=May 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>Avotaynu: the international review of Jewish genealogy, Volume 14, G. Mokotoff, 1998, [https://books.google.com/books?id=77RtAAAAMAAJ&q=Information+comes+from+the+Jewish+communities+of+Antakya+Bodrum+Bursa+Canakkale+Corlu+Edirne+Finike+Gelibolu+Iskendorun+Istanbul+Izmir+Kilis+Kirklarelli+Manisa+and+Tire+plus+a+few+scattered+stones+from+other+Gazi-Antep&dq=Information+comes+from+the+Jewish+communities+of+Antakya+Bodrum+Bursa+Canakkale+Corlu+Edirne+Finike+Gelibolu+Iskendorun+Istanbul+Izmir+Kilis+Kirklarelli+Manisa+and+Tire+plus+a+few+scattered+stones+from+other+Gazi-Antep&hl=en&ei=fbSJTo7lNe7zmAWQyegX&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAA p. 40.]</ref> It has a reputation in Turkey as a place for spells, fortune telling, miracles and spirits.\n\nLocal crafts include a soap scented with the oil of [[bay Laurel|bay tree]].\n\n==Geography==\nAntakya is located on the banks of the [[Orontes River]] ({{lang-tr|Asi Nehri}}), approximately {{convert|22|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} inland from the [[Mediterranean]] coast. The city is in a valley surrounded by mountains, the [[Nur Mountains]] (ancient Amanos) to the north and Mount Kelda\u011f (Jebel Akra) to the south, with the 440 m high Mount Habib-i Neccar (the ancient Mount Silpius) forming its eastern limits. The mountains are a source of a green [[marble]]. Antakya is at the northern edge of the [[Dead Sea Rift]] and vulnerable to earthquakes.\n\nThe plain of [[Amik]] to the north-east of the city is fertile soil watered by the Orontes, the [[Karasu (Hatay)|Karasu]] and the [[Afrin River|Afrin]] rivers; the lake in the plain was drained in 1980 by a French company. At the same time channels were built to widen the Orontes and let it pass neatly through the city centre. The Orontes is joined in Antakya by the Hac\u0131 K\u00fcr\u00fc\u015f stream to the north-east of the city near the church of St Peter, and the Ham\u015fen which runs down from Habib-i Neccar to the south-west, under Memekli Bridge near the army barracks. Flora includes the [[bay Laurel|bay tree]]s and [[Myrtle (plant)|myrtle]].\n\n===Climate===\n\nThe city enjoys a [[hot-summer Mediterranean climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Csa'') with hot and dry summers, and mild and wet winters; however due to its higher altitude, Antakya has slightly cooler temperatures than the coast.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Antakya\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high F = 51\n|Feb high F = 57\n|Mar high F = 64\n|Apr high F = 71\n|May high F = 78\n|Jun high F = 82\n|Jul high F = 86\n|Aug high F = 87\n|Sep high F = 86\n|Oct high F = 80\n|Nov high F = 68\n|Dec high F = 55\n|year high F = 71\n|Jan low F = 39\n|Feb low F = 41\n|Mar low F = 46\n|Apr low F = 51\n|May low F = 59\n|Jun low F = 68\n|Jul low F = 73\n|Aug low F = 75\n|Sep low F = 68\n|Oct low F = 57\n|Nov low F = 46\n|Dec low F = 41\n|year low F = 55\n|Jan precipitation inch = 7.5\n|Feb precipitation inch = 6.5\n|Mar precipitation inch = 5.6\n|Apr precipitation inch = 4.2\n|May precipitation inch = 3.2\n|Jun precipitation inch = 1.3\n|Jul precipitation inch = 0.3\n|Aug precipitation inch = 0.2\n|Sep precipitation inch = 1.1\n|Oct precipitation inch = 3.5\n|Nov precipitation inch = 4.3\n|Dec precipitation inch = 7.5\n|year precipitation inch = 45.1\n|source 1 = Weatherbase<ref name=Weatherbase>{{cite web\n| url =http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=173702&refer=&units=us |title =Weatherbase: Weather for Antakya, Turkey | publisher=Weatherbase | year=2011 }} Retrieved on November 22, 2011.</ref>\n|date=November 2011\n}}\n\n==Education==\n[[Mustafa Kemal University]], abbreviated as MKU, has several faculties including Engineering and Medicine, while having a campus called Tayfur S\u00f6kmen located in Serinyol district {{convert|15|km|mi|abbr=on}}, north of Antakya (centrum).\nEstablished in 1992, currently more than 32,000 students enrolled at the university.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mku.edu.tr/main.php?page=readpage&id=980&location=oidb |publisher=MKU |title=About Mustafa Kemal University (MKU) |accessdate=2011-03-26 }}</ref>\n\nBesides the campus in Serinyol, MKU has its faculties spread out in all main districts of the province including Alt\u0131n\u00f6z\u00fc, Antakya, Belen, D\u00f6rtyol, Erzin, Hassa, \u0130skenderun, K\u0131r\u0131khan, Reyhanl\u0131, Samanda\u011f and Yaylada\u011f\u0131.\n\n==Main sights==\nThe long and varied history has created many architectural sites of interest. There is much for visitors to see in Antakya, although many buildings have been lost in the rapid growth and redevelopment of the city in recent decades.\n* [[Hatay Archaeology Museum]] has the second largest collection of [[Roman Empire|Roman]] [[mosaics]] in the world.\n* The rock-carved ''[[Church of St Peter]]'', with its network of refuges and tunnels carved out of the rock, a site of Christian pilgrimage. There are also tombs cut into the rock face at various places along the Orontes valley.\n*Old market district: It offers plenty of traditional shops, where you can explore what you have not seen before. It is exactly in the city centre, you are in when you see the sign ''Uzun \u00c7ar\u015f\u0131 Caddesi''.\n* The seedy ''G\u00fcnd\u00fcz cinema'' in the city centre was once used as parliament building of the [[Republic of Hatay]].\n* The waterfalls at the [[Harbiye, Antakya|Harbiye]] / Daphne promenade.\n* The [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] ''Habib-i Neccar Camii'', the oldest mosque in Antakya and one of the oldest in [[Anatolia]].\n* The labyrinth of narrow streets and old Antakya houses. This district is the oldtown in fact.\n* [[Vespasianus Titus Tunnel]]-Samandag\u0131. It is approximately 35&nbsp;km. far from the centre.\n* Be\u015fikli Cave and Graves (the antique city of Seleukeia Pierria)\n* St. Simon Monastery\n* [[Bagras|Bagras (Bakras) Castle]], which was built in antiquity and restored many times in later centuries (particularly during the [[Crusades]], when it was a stronghold of the [[Knights Templar]]), served as a watchtower on the {{convert|27|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} mountain road from [[\u0130skenderun]] (Alexandretta) to Antakya (Antioch).\n* The panoramic view of the city from the heights of Mount Habib-i Neccar\n[[File:ANTAKYA EYL\u00dcL 2011 - panoramio (1).jpg|thumb|St. Paul Orthodox Church.]]\n* St. Paul Orthodox Church\n\nWith its rich architectural heritage, Antakya is a member of the [[Norwich]]-based [[European Association of Historic Towns and Regions]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20090917224421/http://www.historic-towns.org/documents/members/turkey.doc]. The Roman bridge (thought to date from the era of [[Diocletian]]) was destroyed in 1972 during the widening and channelling of the [[Orontes River|Orontes]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}\n\n{{wide image|Antioch Panorama Saint Pierre Church.jpg|900px|align-cap=center|A panoramic view of Antakya from the Church of Saint Peter}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Antakya view 1.jpg|Antakya view\nFile:Antakya view 3.jpg|Antakya view\nFile:Antakya view 6156.jpg|Antakya view\nFile:Antakya Yeni Camii 6216.jpg|Antakya Yeni Camii Exterior\nFile:Antakya Yeni Camii 7350.jpg|Antakya Yeni Camii Interior\nFile:Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii 088.jpg|Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii Interior\nFile:Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii 5859.jpg|Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii Exterior\nFile:Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii 7786.jpg|Antakya Habib-i Neccar Camii Exterior\nFile:Antakya Mahremiye camii 2357.jpg|Antakya Mahremiye camii Minaret and top gate\nFile:Antakya Mahremiye camii 2358.jpg|Antakya Mahremiye camii Interior\nFile:Antakya Mahremiye camii 7377.jpg|Antakya Mahremiye camii Minaret and gate\nFile:Antakya Sarimiye Mosque 2711.jpg|Antakya Sarimiye Mosque Minaret\nFile:Antakya Ulu Cami 6228.jpg|Antakya Ulu Cami Entrance to courtyard\nFile:Antakya Ulu Cami 7312.jpg|Antakya Ulu Cami\nFile:Antakya Ulu Cami 7316.jpg|Antakya Ulu Cami\nFile:Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas, Antakya (Antioch).jpg|View of the river in the 1780s, by [[Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas]].\nFile:Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas, Antioche, appeler par les Arabes Anthakyeh, Vue de la pote Bab El Medynah.jpg|Medina gate in the 1780s, by [[Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas]].\n\nFile:Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas, Antioche, appeler par les Arabes Anthakyeh.jpg|Ruins of the Seleucus palace in the 1780s, by [[Louis-Fran\u00e7ois Cassas]].\n\n\n\n\n</gallery>\n\n== Transport ==\nThe city is served from [[Hatay Airport]].\n\n==Sports==\nAntakya has one male professional [[Association football|football]] club, [[Hatayspor]], who play in the [[TFF First League|TFF 1. Lig]]. There is also a female professional team called [[Hatay B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyesi (women's football)|Hatay B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyesi]]. [[Hatay B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyespor (women's basketball)|Hatay B\u00fcy\u00fck\u015fehir Belediyespor]], a woman's basketball team, is also present, and plays in the [[Turkish Women's Basketball League]].\n\n==Cuisine==\nThe cuisine of Antakya is renowned. Its cuisine is considered [[Levantine cuisine|levantine]] rather than [[Turkish cuisine|Turkish]]. The cuisine offers plenty of meals, where beef and lambs are mainly used. Popular dishes include the typical Turkish ''[[kebab]]'', served with spices and onions in flat unleavened bread, with yoghurt as ''ali nazik'' kebab, oruk, kaytaz b\u00f6re\u011fi and kat\u0131kl\u0131 ekmek . Hot spicy food is a feature of this part of Turkey, along with [[Turkish coffee]] and local specialities. Here are some savour:\n\n* ''\u0130\u00e7li k\u00f6fte'' and other [[oruk]] varieties: varieties of the Arabic ''[[kibbeh]]'', deep-fried balls of [[bulgur]] wheat stuffed with minced meat; or baked in ovens in cylinder-cone shape. Sa\u00e7 oru\u011fu is made of the same ingredients, however in circular shape. \n*''Kaytaz b\u00f6re\u011fi'': It is patty that is made of wheat, beef, tomato and onion.\n*''Kat\u0131kl\u0131 ekmek'': Ingredients in Kat\u0131kl\u0131 Ekmek usually consist of wheat, traditional pepper (paste), spices such as sesame and theme, \u00e7\u00f6kelek or cheese. It looks like an ancestor of pizza. Not a lot of restaurants serve it, however it can be found in old-market that is located in the centre and Harbiye.\n* [[Pomegranate]] syrup, used as a salad dressing, called ''debes ramman'', a traditional [[Levantine cuisine|Levantine Arabic]] dressing.\n* ''Semirsek'', a thin bread with hot [[Capsicum|pepper]], minced meat or spinach filling\n* Spicy chicken, a specialty of Harbiye\n* [[Za'atar]] (Zahter) a traditional [[Levantine Arabic]] paste of spiced thyme, oregano, and sesame seeds, mixed with olive oil, spread on flat (called ''pide'' or in English pita) bread.\n* Fresh [[chick peas]], munched as a snack.\n* ''[[Harees|Hirise]]'', boiled and pounded wheat meal.\n* ''A\u015fur'', meat mixed with crushed wheat, chickpea, cumin, onion, pepper and walnut\n\n;''[[Meze]]''\n* [[Hummus]] - the chick-pea dip\n* pureed [[fava beans]]\n* [[Patl\u0131can salatas\u0131]]: Patl\u0131can salatas\u0131 or babaganoush, made of baked and sliced aubergines that mixed\nwith pepper and tomato. It is usually served with pomegranate syrup.\n* [[Taratur]]: Known also as Tarator, made of walnuts, 'tahin', yogurt and garlic. \n* ''S\u00fczme yo\u011furt'': A type of yogurt that its water content is removed with traditional methods.\n* ''Ezme biber'': It is made of pepper and walnuts.\n* [[Surke]] - dried [[curds]] served in spicy olive oil\n* ''\u00c7\u00f6kelek'' - the spicy sun-dried cheese\n* [[Eel]]s from the Orontes, spiced and fried in [[olive oil]]\n\n;Sweets/desserts\n* ''[[Kanafeh|K\u00fcnefe]]'' - a hot cheese, ''kadaif''-based sweet. Antakya is Turkey's ''k\u00fcnefe'' capital; the pastry shops in the centre compete to claim being kings {{lang-tr|kral}} of the pastry.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* ''M\u00fc\u015febbek'' - rings of deep fried pastry.\n* ''Peynirli irmik helvas\u0131'' - Peynirli \u0130rmik Helvas\u0131 is a dessert that is made of semolina, sugar and traditional cheese that is the same as used in k\u00fcnefe. It is served warm, especially in restaurants in the region Harbiye, rather than k\u00fcnefe shops that are located in the centre.\n\n== Twin towns ==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Turkey}}\n\nAntakya is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Aalen]], [[Germany]] (since 1995).\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Alexandros of Antioch|Alexandros]] (1st century BC) Greek sculptor\n*[[George of Antioch]]\n*[[Ignatius of Antioch]], Patriarch of Antioch\n*[[John Chrysostom]] (349\u2013407) Patriarch of Constantinople\n* [[Saint Luke]], 1st century AD, Christian evangelist and author of the [[Gospel of St. Luke]] and [[Acts of the Apostles]]\n*[[Ya\u011f\u0131s\u0131yan]], [[Seljukid]] governor of the city up to its capture by the Crusaders \n* [[Sel\u00e2hattin \u00dclk\u00fcmen]] - [[Righteous among the nations]]\n*[[Tayfur S\u00f6kmen]] - The president of the [[Republic of Hatay]] during its existence between the years 1938 and 1939.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{Cite book|title = Ancient Antioch |author=Glanville Downey|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|year=1963}}\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Antioch|volume=2|pages=130-132|first=William Walker|last=Rockwell|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikivoyage|Antakya}}\n* [http://www.pbase.com/dosseman/Antakya Pictures of Antakya]\n* [http://www.pbase.com/dosseman/antakya_museum Pictures of Antakya Museum]\n\n{{Districts of Turkey|provname=Hatay|image=Hatay|sortkey=Antakya}}\n{{Characters and names in the Quran}}\n{{Metropolitan municipalities in Turkey}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Antakya|*]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Hatay Province]]\n[[Category:\u00c7ukurova]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Hatay Province]]\n[[Category:Populated places along the Silk Road]]\n[[Category:Crusade places]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek archaeological sites in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Seleucid colonies in Anatolia]]\n[[Category:Holy cities]]\n[[Category:New Testament places]]\n[[Category:Roman sites in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 4th century BC]]\n[[Category:Jewish communities in Turkey]]\n[[Category:300s BC establishments]]\n", "name_user": "Konli17", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCrusader era", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antakya"}
{"title_page": "The Handmaiden", "text_new": "{{About|the 2016 South Korean film|the servant|handmaiden|other uses|The Handmaid (disambiguation){{!}}The Handmaid}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Handmaiden\n| image          = The Handmaiden film.png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| film name      = {{Film name\n| hangul         = {{linktext|\uc544\uac00\uc528}}\n| rr             = Agassi}}\n| director       = [[Park Chan-wook]]\n| producer       = {{Plain list|\n* Park Chan-wook\n* Syd Lim\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* Park Chan-wook\n* Chung Seo-kyung\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Fingersmith (novel)|Fingersmith]]''|[[Sarah Waters]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Kim Min-hee (actress, born 1982)|Kim Min-hee]]\n* [[Kim Tae-ri]]\n* [[Ha Jung-woo]]\n* [[Cho Jin-woong]]\n}}\n| music           = [[Jo Yeong-wook]]\n| cinematography  = [[Chung Chung-hoon]]\n| editing         = {{plainlist|\n* Kim Jae-bum\n* [[Kim Sang-bum (film editor)|Kim Sang-bum]]\n}}\n| production companies = {{plainlist|\n* Moho Film\n* Yong Film\n}}\n| distributor     = [[CJ Entertainment]]\n| released        = {{film date|2016|5|14|[[2016 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2016|6|1|[[South Korea]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime         = {{plainlist|\n* 145 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/handmaiden-film | title=''The Handmaiden'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref>\n* 168 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/handmaiden-directors-cut-film | title=''The Handmaiden: Director's Cut'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> {{small|([[Director's cut]])}}\n}}\n| country         = South Korea\n| language        = {{plainlist|\n* Korean\n* Japanese\n}}\n| budget          = [[Won sign|\u20a9]]10 billion<br>(approx. [[United States dollar|$]]8.8 million)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4016934/business?ref_=tt_dt_bus|title=Box office / business for Ah-ga-ssi|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n| gross           = $38.6 million<ref name=\"NUM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/A-Ga-ssi-(S-Korea)#tab=summary|title=A Ga ssi (2016)|website=The Numbers|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=thehandmaiden.htm|title=The Handmaiden (2016)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Handmaiden''''' ({{ko-hhrm|\uc544\uac00\uc528||Agassi}}; {{literal translation|\"Lady\"}}) is a 2016 South Korean [[Erotic thriller|erotic]] [[psychological thriller]] film directed by [[Park Chan-wook]] and starring [[Kim Min-hee (actress, born 1982)|Kim Min-hee]], [[Kim Tae-ri]], [[Ha Jung-woo]] and [[Cho Jin-woong]]. It is inspired by the novel ''[[Fingersmith (novel)|Fingersmith]]'' by Welsh writer [[Sarah Waters]], with the setting changed from [[Victorian era]] Britain to [[Korea under Japanese rule|Korea under Japanese colonial rule]].\n\nThe film was selected to compete for the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]]. It was released in South Korea on 1 June 2016, to critical acclaim. It grossed over $38 million worldwide.\n\nAt the [[71st British Academy Film Awards]], the film won the category of [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language|Best Film Not in the English Language]].\n\n==Plot==\n===Part 1===\nIn [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese-occupied Korea]], a con man operating under the [[sobriquet]] of \"Count [[Fujiwara clan|Fujiwara]]\" plans to seduce a Japanese heiress named Lady Hideko, then marry her and commit her to an asylum in order to steal her inheritance. He hires a pickpocket named Sook-hee to become Hideko's maid and encourage Hideko to marry him.\n\nHideko lives with her Uncle Kouzuki, a Korean man who [[Chinilpa|helped the Japanese take over his country]] in exchange for a gold mine. Kouzuki then uses this wealth to feed his obsession with rare books, selling forgeries to further accumulate money and books. Sook-hee's main job is to help Hideko prepare to read for Kouzuki's guests. Returning frustrated from a reading, Hideko demands Sook-hee sleep next to her. The two end up making love, under the pretext of preparing Hideko for her married life with the Count. Sook-hee begins expressing reluctance about the plan, but when Hideko herself suggests she loves someone other than the Count, Sook-hee insists on the marriage. Hideko slaps her and violently throws her from the room. \n\nWhen Kouzuki leaves on business for a week, Hideko and Fujiwara elope. After cashing out Hideko's inheritance, it is revealed that Hideko's na\u00efvet\u00e9 was part of the con. She and Fujiwara double-crossed Sook-hee and convinced the asylum that she is the \"Countess\" to have her committed in Hideko's stead.\n\n===Part 2===\nA series of flashbacks show that Hideko's \u201creading practice\u201d was in fact Kouzuki teaching her to erotically read sadistic pornography since she was five years old. The flashbacks show a regime of psychological and physical abuse that eventually degrades Hideko's aunt's sanity. Hideko's aunt is eventually found hanged from a tree in the yard, and Hideko takes over as the reader for the pornography auctions. When Hideko questions the description of a hanging in a book she has to read, Kouzuki tells her that he murdered her aunt using torture devices in the basement after she attempted to run away.\n\nIn the more recent past, the Count realizes seducing Hideko would be impossible and instead includes her in the plan to elope and then split her inheritance. When Hideko expresses her fear of her uncle, the Count promises her a vial of fast-acting poison as a wedding present, so that she can never be taken to the basement. Hideko demands the Count find her a girl to hire as a maid, to commit to an asylum in Hideko's place.\n\nWhile being instructed by the Count, who takes advantage of Sook-hee's illiteracy, Hideko unexpectedly falls in love with her. Hideko tries to confess her love, but when Sook-hee insists the marriage go on, Hideko throws her from the room and tries to hang herself. Sook-hee saves her and both admit to their plots. Hideko helps Sook-hee write a letter to her family to say she has teamed up with Hideko, and to hatch a plot to get Hideko and Sook-hee away from the men who have been manipulating them. Hideko shows Sook-hee the books she was forced to read and Sook-hee begins destroying the library. Hideko calls Sook-hee \"her savior\" and joins in destroying her uncle's collection.\n\n===Part 3===\nSook-hee's friend Bok-soon sets a fire at the asylum and poses as a firefighter to rescue Sook-hee. Hideko poisons Fujiwara's wine, causing him to pass out while she takes the money and leaves. The women reunite and flee together, disguising Hideko as a man to avoid detection.\n\nKouzuki captures Fujiwara upon receiving a letter from Hideko detailing Fujiwara's deception. He tortures Fujiwara in his cellar with his collection of antique bookmaking tools and presses him for sexual details about his niece. Fujiwara makes up a story about their wedding night but a flashback shows that he watched Hideko masturbate before cutting her hand on a knife to stain her sheets, refusing to consummate the marriage. When Kouzuki presses for more details, Fujiwara convinces him to give him one of his cigarettes. After smoking, a disgusted Fujiwara refuses to give further details. Kouzuki notices the cigarettes are producing blue smoke. Fujiwara reveals that his cigarettes had been laced with mercury and the toxic gas within the smoke kills them both.\n\nOn a ferry to [[Shanghai, China]], Sook-hee and Hideko celebrate their newfound freedom by making love once again.\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Kim Min-hee (actress, born 1982)|Kim Min-hee]] as Lady/Izumi Hideko\n* [[Kim Tae-ri]] as Maid/Nam Sook-hee\n* [[Ha Jung-woo]] as Count Fujiwara\n* [[Cho Jin-woong]] as Uncle Kouzuki\n* [[Kim Hae-sook]] as Butler Madame Sasaki\n* [[Moon So-ri]] as Hideko's aunt\n* Lee Yong-nyeo as Bok-soon\n* [[Lee Dong-hwi]] as Goo-gai\n* Jo Eun-hyung as young Hideko\n* Rina Takagi as Hideko's mother\n* Han Ha-na as Junko\n* [[Jeong Ha-dam]] as Housemaid\n* [[Choi Byung-mo]] as Audience member\n}}\n\n==Production==\nIn December 2014, it was reported that Kim Min-hee, Kim Tae-ri, Ha Jung-woo and Cho Jin-woong signed on for the film.<ref name=fingersmith2014>{{cite web|first1=June|last1=Kim|title=KIM Min-hee and KIM Tae-ri Confirmed for FINGERSMITH|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/news/news.jsp?mode=VIEW&seq=3255|website=Korean Film Biz Zone|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=1 December 2014}}</ref> Kim Tae-ri was selected from 1,500 candidates to play the role.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jin|first1=Eun-soo|title=''The Handmaiden'' generates a buzz|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3018243|website=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|accessdate=10 May 2016|date=3 May 2016}}</ref> Shooting for the film began in June 2015 and concluded in October 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Oldboy'' Director Park Chan-wook Starts Lesbian ''Fingersmith'' Adaptation|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/asia/park-chan-wook-lesbian-fingersmith-1201524738/|accessdate=November 14, 2015|date=June 21, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last1=Kil|first=Sonia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=First Look at Park Chan-wook's Fingersmith Adaptation The Handmaid|url=http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/first-look-at-park-chan-wooks-fingersmith-adaptation-the-handmaid-248|accessdate=November 14, 2015|date=November 3, 2015|work=[[JoBlo.com]]|last=Giroux|first=Jesse}}</ref>\n\nThe books ''[[The Dream of the Fisherman's Wife]]'' and ''[[Jin Ping Mei]]'' were featured in the film.<ref name=\"economistreview\"/>\n\n== Release ==\nIn February 2016, CJ Entertainment announced that ''The Handmaiden'' was pre-sold to 116 countries, including to [[Amazon Studios]] for the US.<ref name=\"Noh\">{{cite web |url= http://www.screendaily.com/news/park-chan-wooks-handmaiden-pre-sells-to-116-countries/5100808.article|title= Park Chan-wook's ''Handmaiden'' pre-sells to 116 countries|first= Jean|last= Noh|date=24 February 2016|accessdate=25 February 2016|work= [[Screen Daily]]}}</ref> The film premiered in competition at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]], where it received a standing ovation, and Ryu Seong-hee won the [[Vulcan Award]] of the Technical Artist for her art direction work on the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/park-chan-wook-handmaiden-homosexuality-893716|title=Park Chan-Wook Talks 'The Handmaiden', Homosexuality Onscreen and Korean Films' Specific Appeal (Q&A)|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpopherald.com/view.php?ud=201605151328147065449_2|work=Herald Corporation|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=\u2018The Handmaiden\u2019 receives standing ovation at Cannes|date=May 15, 2016|first=Jung|last=Min-kyung}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/actualites/articles/69th-festival-de-cannes-awards|work=Festival de Cannes|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=69th Festival de Cannes Awards|date=May 22, 2016}}</ref> The film was also screened in the Special Presentations section of the [[2016 Toronto International Film Festival]], where ''[[The Playlist]]'' named it as one of the 15 best films of the festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theplaylist.net/15-best-films-2016-toronto-international-film-festival-20160919/|work=The Playlist|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=The 15 Best Films Of The 2016 Toronto International Film Festival|date=September 19, 2016}}</ref> In South Korea, the film was released on 1 June 2016 and sold more than 4 million tickets.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/south-korea-box-office-cannes-900292|title=South Korea Box Office: Cannes Hit 'The Handmaiden' Tops 'X-Men: Apocalypse'|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-competition-entry-handmaiden-best-895683|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=3 January 2016|title=Cannes: Competition Entry 'The Handmaiden' Best-Selling Korean Film of All Time|date=19 May 2016|first=Lee|last=Hyo-won}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/news/boxOffice_Yearly.jsp?mode=BOXOFFICE_YEAR&selectDt=2016&category=ALL&country=ALL|work=KOFIC|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=Yearly BoxOffice [2016]}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, the distribution of the film was handled by Amazon Studios and [[Magnolia Pictures]]. The film opened in [[limited release]] across five cinemas in [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2016/10/arthouse-audit-moonlight-box-office-record-the-handmaiden-1201739455/|work=[[Indiewire]]|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=Arthouse Audit: \u2018Moonlight\u2019 Soars to Near-Record Levels; \u2018The Handmaiden\u2019 Beats the Odds|date=October 23, 2016|first=Brueggemann|last=Tom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/10/moonlight-king-cobra-michael-moore-trumpland-specialty-box-office-1201841247/|work=Deadline|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=\u2018Moonlight\u2019 & \u2018Michael Moore In TrumpLand\u2019 Top 2016 Theater Averages \u2013 Specialty B.O.|date=October 23, 2016|first=Brooks|last=Brian}}</ref> and played in 140 additional cinemas in the following weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreadailyus.com/park-chan-wooks-new-erotic-thriller-the-handmaiden-opens-in-us-theaters/|work=The Korea Daily |accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=Park Chan-wook\u2019s New Erotic Thriller, The Handmaiden, Opens in US Theaters|date=October 21, 2016|first=Kim|last=Heewon}}</ref> Eventually, the film grossed more than $2 million in the United States theatrically;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=thehandmaiden.htm|title=The Handmaiden (2016)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> the film outgrossed ''[[Stoker (film)|Stoker]]'' and became the highest-grossing Park Chan-wook-directed film in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=stoker.htm|title=Stoker (2013) - Box Office Mojo|website=Boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>  It was released on DVD in the US on 24 January 2017 and Blu-ray on March 28, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flavorwire.com/597707/the-5-best-movies-to-buy-or-stream-this-week-the-handmaiden-the-light-between-oceans|work=Flavorwire |accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=The 5 Best Movies to Buy or Stream This Week: \u2018The Handmaiden,\u2019 \u2018The Man Who Fell to Earth\u2019|date=January 24, 2017|first=Bailey|last= Jason}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/8313/the-handmaiden|work=Dvdsreleasedates |accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=The Handmaiden (2016)}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, the distribution of the film was handled by Amazon Studios and [[Curzon Artificial Eye]]. The film grossed more than $1.8 million in the United Kingdom theatrically, and became the highest-grossing foreign-language film in the UK in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/features/uk-box-office-2017-verdict-a-strong-year-despite-us-downturn/5125146.article|title=UK box office 2017 verdict: a strong year despite US downturn|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n===Critical response===\n''The Handmaiden'' received critical acclaim. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an [[approval rating]] of 95%, based on 206 reviews, and an average score of 8.3/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''The Handmaiden'' uses a Victorian crime novel as the loose inspiration for another visually sumptuous and absorbingly idiosyncratic outing from director Park Chan-wook.\"<ref name=\"Rotten\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_handmaiden/|title=The Handmaiden|accessdate=23 November 2018|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds a [[weighted average]] score of 84 out of 100, based on 40 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-handmaiden|title=The Handmaiden|accessdate=3 July 2017|website=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref> ''[[The Economist]]'' described the film as a masterpiece.<ref name=\"economistreview\">{{cite news|author1=K.S.C.|title=\"The Handmaiden\": a new masterpiece from Park Chan-wook|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2017/04/korean-film|accessdate=17 April 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|date=13 April 2017}}</ref> Benjamin Lee of ''[[The Guardian]]'' ranked it four out of five stars and described it as \"a hugely entertaining thriller\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Lee, Benjamin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/may/14/the-handmaiden-review-park-chan-wooks-lurid-lesbian-potboiler-simmers-with-sexual-tension|title=The Handmaiden review \u2013 Park Chan-wook's lurid lesbian potboiler simmers with sexual tension |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=2016-05-14|accessdate=2018-11-16}}</ref>\n\n===Response to the explicit scenes===\nThe film's numerous sexually explicit scenes between the two main female characters sparked some controversy. Laura Miller at ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' described the scenes as \"disappointingly boilerplate\" and featuring \"visual clich\u00e9s of pornographic lesbianism, [the actresses'] bodies offered up for the camera\u2019s delectation.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Laura|title=The Handmaiden Park Chan-wook takes on Sarah Waters\u2019 brilliant, intricate novel Fingersmith|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2016/10/park_chan_wook_s_the_handmaiden_based_on_sarah_waters_fingersmith_reviewed.html|website=Slate|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref> However, The [[New Yorker (magazine)|''New Yorker'']]'s Jia Tolentino said that \"the women know what they look like, it seems\u2014they are consciously performing for each other\u2014and Park is deft at extracting the particular sense of silly freedom that can be found in enacting a sexual clich\u00e9.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tolentino|first1=Jia|title=\"The Handmaiden\" and the Freedom Women Find Only with One Another|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/jia-tolentino/the-handmaiden-and-the-freedom-women-find-only-with-one-another|accessdate=3 December 2017|agency=The New Yorker|publisher=Conde Nast|date=2016-10-26}}</ref>\n\n===Top ten lists===\n''The Handmaiden'' was listed on numerous critics' top ten lists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-list-the-top-10-movies-of-2016|title=Best of 2016: Film Critic Top Ten Lists|website=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Danny Bowes, ''[[RogerEbert.com]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Dan Callahan, ''RogerEbert.com''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Noel Murray & Katie Rife, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Rob Hunter, ''[[Film School Rejects]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Sean Mulvihill, ''RogerEbert.com''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Tasha Robinson, ''[[The Verge]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 William Bibbiani, ''[[CraveOnline]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 Amy Nicholson, ''[[MTV]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 Witney Seibold, ''[[CraveOnline]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 Jen Yamato, ''[[The Daily Beast]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 [[James Berardinelli]], ''Reelviews''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 [[Bilge Ebiri]], ''[[L.A. Weekly]]''\n* 4th&nbsp;\u2013 Kimberley Jones, ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''\n* 4th&nbsp;\u2013 Scott Tobias, ''[[Village Voice]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/filmpoll/view/critics/Scott+Tobias/2016 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-02-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205182012/http://www.villagevoice.com/filmpoll/view/critics/Scott%2BTobias/2016 |archive-date=2017-02-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Lean Pickett, ''[[Chicago Reader]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Kate Taylor, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Josh Kupecki, ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Haleigh Foutch, ''[[Collider (website)|Collider]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Erin Whitney, ''ScreenCrush''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Peter Freeman, ''DC Outlook<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dcoutlook.com/2016/12/dc-outlooks-top-10-movies-of-2016.html|title=DC Outlook's Top 10 Movies of 2016|website=Dcoutlook.com|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 Sean Axmaker, ''Parallax View''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 John Powers, ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Alonso Duralde]], ''[[TheWrap]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Christy Lemire]] and Peter Sobczynski, ''RogerEbert.com''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 Mike D\u2019Angelo & A.A. Dowd, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 7th&nbsp;\u2013 Bill Goodykoontz, ''[[The Arizona Republic]]''\n* 7th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Matt Zoller Seitz]] & Brian Tallerico, ''RogerEbert.com''\n* 7th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Christopher Orr (film critic)|Christopher Orr]], ''[[The Atlantic]]''\n* 7th&nbsp;\u2013 Steve Davis, ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013 Matt Singer, ''ScreenCrush''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ty Burr]], ''[[The Boston Globe]]''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Todd McCarthy]], ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Manohla Dargis]], ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013 [[David Edelstein]], ''[[New York Magazine]]''\n* 9th&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[The Guardian]]''\n* 10th&nbsp;\u2013 Marc Savlov, ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''\n* 10th&nbsp;\u2013 Dennis Dermody, ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]''\n* Top 10 (listed alphabetically, not ranked)&nbsp;\u2013  Walter Addiego, ''San Francisco Chronicle''\n{{div col end}}\n\nIn 2019, ''[[The Guardian]]'' ranked ''The Handmaiden'' 41st in its 100 best films of the 21st century list.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 100 best films of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/sep/13/100-best-films-movies-of-the-21st-century |website=The Guardian |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> In 2020, ''The Guardian'' also ranked it number 1 among the classics of modern South Korean Cinema.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|title=Classics of modern South Korean cinema \u2013 ranked! |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/feb/13/classics-of-modern-south-korean-cinema-ranked |website=The Guardian |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"| List of awards and nominations\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"62\"| 2016\n| [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://awfj.org/eda-awards-2/2016-awfj-eda-award-nominees/ |title=2016 AWFJ EDA Award Nominees |first=Jennifer |last=Merin |publisher=[[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]] |date=December 16, 2016 |accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wearemoviegeeks.com/2016/12/arrival-la-la-land-hell-high-water-among-nominees-2016-awfj-eda-awards/ |title='Arrival', 'La La Land', 'Hell or High Water' Among The Nominees for the 2016 AWFJ EDA Awards |first=Michelle |last=McCue |publisher=WeAreMovieGeeks.com |date=December 16, 2016 |accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n| Best Non-English-Language Film\n| [[Park Chan-wook]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[Austin Film Critics Association Awards 2016|Austin Film Critics Association]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awardswatch.com/news/austin-film-critics-association-afca-nominations-the-handmaiden-lands-top-mentions-trevante-rhodes-double-nominated/ |title=Austin Film Critics Association (AFCA) Nominations: The Handmaiden Lands Top Mentions, Trevante Rhodes Double Nominated |first=Erik |last=Anderson |publisher=AwardsWatch.com |date=December 15, 2016 |accessdate=December 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/austin-film-critics-association/2016-nominations-5307a85b7c6a#.yjh64hs3i |title=2016 Austin Film Critics Awards Nominees, 'Moonlight' and 'Arrival' lead the way in AFCA's 2016 nominations |first=Neil |last=Miller |publisher=Medium.com |date=December 15, 2016 |accessdate=December 15, 2016}}</ref>\n| Best Film\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{draw|4th Place}}\n|-\n| Best Director\n| Park Chan-wook\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actress\n| [[Kim Min-hee (actress, born 1982)|Kim Min-hee]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Adapted Screenplay\n| Park Chan-wook and Chung Seo-kyung\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Chung Chung-hoon\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[37th Blue Dragon Film Awards|Blue Dragon Film Awards]]\n| Best Film\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Director\n| Park Chan-wook\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actress\n| Kim Min-hee\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best New Actress\n| [[Kim Tae-ri]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Chung Chung-hoon\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Art Direction\n| Ryu Seong-hee\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Music\n| [[Jo Yeong-wook]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Technical Award\n| Jo Sang-kyeong (costume design)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Awards 2016|Boston Society of Film Critics]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/la-la-land-named-best-picture-by-boston-society-film-critics-955066 |title='La La Land' Named Best Picture by Boston Society of Film Critics |first=Patrick |last=Shanley |date=December 11, 2016 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=December 11, 2016}}</ref>\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| Chung Chung-hoon\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[25th Buil Film Awards|Buil Film Awards]]\n| Best Film\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Director\n| Park Chan-wook\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actress\n| Kim Min-hee\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best New Actress\n| Kim Tae-ri\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Chung Chung-hoon\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Art Direction\n| Ryu Seong-hee\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Music\n| Jo Yeong-wook\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Buil Readers' Jury Award\n| Park Chan-wook\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Busan Film Critics Awards]]\n| Best New Actress\n| Kim Tae-ri\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[2016 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes Film Festival]]\n| [[Palme d'Or]]\n| Park Chan-wook\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Queer Palm\n| Park Chan-wook\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Vulcan Award]]\n| Ryu Seong-hee\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Awards 2016|Chicago Film Critics Association]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chicagofilmcritics.org/component/content/article/148-cfca-nominees-2016 |title=The 2016 Chicago Film Critics Association Award Nominees |date=December 11, 2016 |publisher=[[Chicago Film Critics Association]] |accessdate=December 12, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220200944/http://www.chicagofilmcritics.org/component/content/article/148-cfca-nominees-2016 |archivedate=December 20, 2016 }}</ref>\n| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| Park Chan-wook\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n| Park Chan-wook and Chung Seo-kyung\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| Chung Chung-hoon\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Chicago Film Critics Association Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Art Direction\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[22nd Critics' Choice Awards|Critics' Choice Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=La La Land Leads with 12 Nominations for the 22nd Annual Critics' Choice Awards |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/critics-choice-awards |publisher=Critics' Choice |date=December 1, 2016 |accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n| [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Film Critics Association Awards 2016|Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Film Critics Association]]<ref name=\"DFWFCA\">{{cite web|url=http://dfwcritics.com/dfw-film-critics-name-moonlight-best-film-of-2016/ |title=DFW Film Critics Name 'Moonlight' Best Film of 2016 |publisher=[[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Film Critics Association]] |date=December 13, 2016|accessdate=December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Director's Cut Awards]]\n| Best Actress\n| Kim Min-hee\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best New Actress\n| Kim Tae-ri\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Florida Film Critics Circle Awards 2016|Florida Film Critics Circle]]<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018MOONLIGHT\u2019 LEADS 2016 FLORIDA FILM CRITICS AWARDS NOMINATIONS |url=http://www.floridafilmcritics.com/2016/12/20/moonlight-leads-2016-florida-film-critics-awards-nominations/ |publisher=Florida Film Critics Circle |date=December 21, 2016 |accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref>\n| [[Florida Film Critics Circle Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{draw|Runner-up}}\n|-\n| [[Florida Film Critics Circle Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| Chung Chung-hoon\n| {{draw|Runner-up}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Korean Association of Film Critics Awards]]\n| Top Ten Films of the Year\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Chung Chung-hoon\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| [[IndieWire|IndieWire Critics Poll]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2016/12/best-movies-2016-critic-poll-results-1201757008/ |title=2016 IndieWire Critics Poll: Full List of Results |first=Steve |las