 thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language films]]\n[[Category:Korean-language films]]\n[[Category:South Korean erotic drama films]]\n[[Category:South Korean erotic thriller films]]\n[[Category:South Korean films]]\n[[Category:South Korean LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:South Korean nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:South Korean psychological films]]\n[[Category:South Korean romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:South Korean romantic thriller films]]\n[[Category:Juvenile sexuality in films]]\n[[Category:Lesbian-related films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:LGBT-related thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films about con artists]]\n[[Category:Films based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1930s]]\n[[Category:Films set in Japan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Korea under Japanese rule]]\n[[Category:Films set in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Park Chan-wook]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Language Film BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:CJ Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:South Korean historical films]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 2016 South Korean film|the servant|handmaiden|other uses|The Handmaid (disambiguation){{!}}The Handmaid}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Handmaiden\n| image          = The Handmaiden film.png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| film name      = {{Film name\n| hangul         = {{linktext|\uc544\uac00\uc528}}\n| rr             = Agassi}}\n| director       = [[Park Chan-wook]]\n| producer       = {{Plain list|\n* Park Chan-wook\n* Syd Lim\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* Park Chan-wook\n* Chung Seo-kyung\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Fingersmith (novel)|Fingersmith]]''|[[Sarah Waters]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Kim Min-hee (actress, born 1982)|Kim Min-hee]]\n* [[Kim Tae-ri]]\n* [[Ha Jung-woo]]\n* [[Cho Jin-woong]]\n}}\n| music           = [[Jo Yeong-wook]]\n| cinematography  = [[Chung Chung-hoon]]\n| editing         = {{plainlist|\n* Kim Jae-bum\n* [[Kim Sang-bum (film editor)|Kim Sang-bum]]\n}}\n| production companies = {{plainlist|\n* Moho Film\n* Yong Film\n}}\n| distributor     = [[CJ Entertainment]]\n| released        = {{film date|2016|5|14|[[2016 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2016|6|1|[[South Korea]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime         = {{plainlist|\n* 145 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/handmaiden-film | title=''The Handmaiden'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref>\n* 168 minutes<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/handmaiden-directors-cut-film | title=''The Handmaiden: Director's Cut'' | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> {{small|([[Director's cut]])}}\n}}\n| country         = South Korea\n| language        = {{plainlist|\n* Korean\n* Japanese\n}}\n| budget          = [[Won sign|\u20a9]]10 billion<br>(approx. [[United States dollar|$]]8.8 million)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt4016934/business?ref_=tt_dt_bus|title=Box office / business for Ah-ga-ssi|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n| gross           = $38.6 million<ref name=\"NUM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/A-Ga-ssi-(S-Korea)#tab=summary|title=A Ga ssi (2016)|website=The Numbers|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=thehandmaiden.htm|title=The Handmaiden (2016)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Handmaiden''''' ({{ko-hhrm|\uc544\uac00\uc528||Agassi}}; {{literal translation|\"Lady\"}}) is a 2016 South Korean [[Erotic thriller|erotic]] [[psychological thriller]] film directed by [[Park Chan-wook]] and starring [[Kim Min-hee (actress, born 1982)|Kim Min-hee]], [[Kim Tae-ri]], [[Ha Jung-woo]] and [[Cho Jin-woong]]. It is inspired by the novel ''[[Fingersmith (novel)|Fingersmith]]'' by Welsh writer [[Sarah Waters]], with the setting changed from [[Victorian era]] Britain to [[Korea under Japanese rule|Korea under Japanese colonial rule]].\n\nThe film was selected to compete for the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]]. It was released in South Korea on 1 June 2016, to critical acclaim. It grossed over $38 million worldwide.\n\nAt the [[71st British Academy Film Awards]], the film won the category of [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language|Best Film Not in the English Language]].\n\n==Plot==\n===Part 1===\nIn [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese-occupied Korea]], a con man operating under the [[sobriquet]] of \"Count [[Fujiwara clan|Fujiwara]]\" plans to seduce a Japanese heiress named Lady Hideko, then marry her and commit her to an asylum in order to steal her inheritance. He hires a pickpocket named Sook-hee to become Hideko's maid and encourage Hideko to marry him.\n\nHideko lives with her Uncle Kouzuki, a Korean man who [[Chinilpa|helped the Japanese take over his country]] in exchange for a gold mine. Kouzuki then uses this wealth to feed his obsession with rare books, selling forgeries to further accumulate money and books. Sook-hee\u2019s main job is to help Hideko prepare to read for Kouzuki\u2019s guests. Returning frustrated from a reading, Hideko demands Sook-hee sleep next to her. The two end up making love, under the pretext of preparing Hideko for her married life with the Count. Sook-hee begins expressing reluctance about the plan, but when Hideko herself suggests she loves someone other than the Count, Sook-hee insists on the marriage. Hideko slaps her and violently throws her from the room. \n\nWhen Kouzuki leaves on business for a week, Hideko and Fujiwara elope. After cashing out Hideko's inheritance, it is revealed that Hideko\u2019s na\u00efvet\u00e9 was part of the con. She and Fujiwara double-crossed Sook-hee and convinced the asylum that she is the \"Countess\" to have her committed in Hideko's stead.\n\n===Part 2===\nA series of flashbacks show that Hideko\u2019s \u201creading practice\u201d was in fact Kouzuki teaching her to erotically read sadistic pornography since she was five years old. The flashbacks show a regime of psychological and physical abuse that eventually degrades Hideko\u2019s aunt\u2019s sanity. Hideko's aunt is eventually found hanged from a tree in the yard, and Hideko takes over as the reader for the pornography auctions. When Hideko questions the description of a hanging in a book she has to read, Kouzuki tells her that he murdered her aunt using torture devices in the basement after she attempted to run away.\n\nIn the more recent past, the Count realizes seducing Hideko would be impossible and instead includes her in the plan to elope and then split her inheritance. When Hideko expresses her fear of her uncle, the Count promises her a vial of fast-acting poison as a wedding present, so that she can never be taken to the basement. Hideko demands the Count find her a girl to hire as a maid, to commit to an asylum in Hideko\u2019s place.\n\nWhile being instructed by the Count, who takes advantage of Sook-hee's illiteracy, Hideko unexpectedly falls in love with her. Hideko tries to confess her love, but when Sook-hee insists the marriage go on, Hideko throws her from the room and tries to hang herself. Sook-hee saves her and both admit to their plots. Hideko helps Sook-hee write a letter to her family to say she has teamed up with Hideko, and to hatch a plot to get Hideko and Sook-hee away from the men who have been manipulating them. Hideko shows Sook-hee the books she was forced to read and Sook-hee begins destroying the library. Hideko calls Sook-hee \"her savior\" and joins in destroying her uncle\u2019s collection.\n\n===Part 3===\nSook-hee's friend Bok-soon sets a fire at the asylum and poses as a firefighter to rescue Sook-hee. Hideko poisons Fujiwara's wine, causing him to pass out while she takes the money and leaves. The women reunite and flee together, disguising Hideko as a man to avoid detection.\n\nKouzuki captures Fujiwara upon receiving a letter from Hideko detailing Fujiwara's deception. He tortures Fujiwara in his cellar with his collection of antique bookmaking tools and presses him for sexual details about his niece. Fujiwara makes up a story about their wedding night but a flashback shows that he watched Hideko masturbate before cutting her hand on a knife to stain her sheets, refusing to consummate the marriage. When Kouzuki presses for more details, Fujiwara convinces him to give him one of his cigarettes. After smoking, a disgusted Fujiwara refuses to give further details. Kouzuki notices the cigarettes are producing blue smoke. Fujiwara reveals that his cigarettes had been laced with mercury and the toxic gas within the smoke kills them both.\n\nOn a ferry to [[Shanghai, China]], Sook-hee and Hideko celebrate their newfound freedom by making love once again.\n\n==Cast==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Kim Min-hee (actress, born 1982)|Kim Min-hee]] as Lady/Izumi Hideko\n* [[Kim Tae-ri]] as Maid/Nam Sook-hee\n* [[Ha Jung-woo]] as Count Fujiwara\n* [[Cho Jin-woong]] as Uncle Kouzuki\n* [[Kim Hae-sook]] as Butler Madame Sasaki\n* [[Moon So-ri]] as Hideko's aunt\n* Lee Yong-nyeo as Bok-soon\n* [[Lee Dong-hwi]] as Goo-gai\n* Jo Eun-hyung as young Hideko\n* Rina Takagi as Hideko's mother\n* Han Ha-na as Junko\n* [[Jeong Ha-dam]] as Housemaid\n* [[Choi Byung-mo]] as Audience member\n}}\n\n==Production==\nIn December 2014, it was reported that Kim Min-hee, Kim Tae-ri, Ha Jung-woo and Cho Jin-woong signed on for the film.<ref name=fingersmith2014>{{cite web|first1=June|last1=Kim|title=KIM Min-hee and KIM Tae-ri Confirmed for FINGERSMITH|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/news/news.jsp?mode=VIEW&seq=3255|website=Korean Film Biz Zone|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=1 December 2014}}</ref> Kim Tae-ri was selected from 1,500 candidates to play the role.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jin|first1=Eun-soo|title=''The Handmaiden'' generates a buzz|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3018243|website=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|accessdate=10 May 2016|date=3 May 2016}}</ref> Shooting for the film began in June 2015 and concluded in October 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Oldboy'' Director Park Chan-wook Starts Lesbian ''Fingersmith'' Adaptation|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/asia/park-chan-wook-lesbian-fingersmith-1201524738/|accessdate=November 14, 2015|date=June 21, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last1=Kil|first=Sonia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=First Look at Park Chan-wook's Fingersmith Adaptation The Handmaid|url=http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/first-look-at-park-chan-wooks-fingersmith-adaptation-the-handmaid-248|accessdate=November 14, 2015|date=November 3, 2015|work=[[JoBlo.com]]|last=Giroux|first=Jesse}}</ref>\n\nThe books ''[[The Dream of the Fisherman's Wife]]'' and ''[[Jin Ping Mei]]'' were featured in the film.<ref name=\"economistreview\"/>\n\n== Release ==\nIn February 2016, CJ Entertainment announced that ''The Handmaiden'' was pre-sold to 116 countries, including to [[Amazon Studios]] for the US.<ref name=\"Noh\">{{cite web |url= http://www.screendaily.com/news/park-chan-wooks-handmaiden-pre-sells-to-116-countries/5100808.article|title= Park Chan-wook's ''Handmaiden'' pre-sells to 116 countries|first= Jean|last= Noh|date=24 February 2016|accessdate=25 February 2016|work= [[Screen Daily]]}}</ref> The film premiered in competition at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]], where it received a standing ovation, and Ryu Seong-hee won the [[Vulcan Award]] of the Technical Artist for her art direction work on the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/park-chan-wook-handmaiden-homosexuality-893716|title=Park Chan-Wook Talks 'The Handmaiden', Homosexuality Onscreen and Korean Films' Specific Appeal (Q&A)|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpopherald.com/view.php?ud=201605151328147065449_2|work=Herald Corporation|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=\u2018The Handmaiden\u2019 receives standing ovation at Cannes|date=May 15, 2016|first=Jung|last=Min-kyung}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/actualites/articles/69th-festival-de-cannes-awards|work=Festival de Cannes|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=69th Festival de Cannes Awards|date=May 22, 2016}}</ref> The film was also screened in the Special Presentations section of the [[2016 Toronto International Film Festival]], where ''[[The Playlist]]'' named it as one of the 15 best films of the festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theplaylist.net/15-best-films-2016-toronto-international-film-festival-20160919/|work=The Playlist|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=The 15 Best Films Of The 2016 Toronto International Film Festival|date=September 19, 2016}}</ref> In South Korea, the film was released on 1 June 2016 and sold more than 4 million tickets.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/south-korea-box-office-cannes-900292|title=South Korea Box Office: Cannes Hit 'The Handmaiden' Tops 'X-Men: Apocalypse'|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-competition-entry-handmaiden-best-895683|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=3 January 2016|title=Cannes: Competition Entry 'The Handmaiden' Best-Selling Korean Film of All Time|date=19 May 2016|first=Lee|last=Hyo-won}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/news/boxOffice_Yearly.jsp?mode=BOXOFFICE_YEAR&selectDt=2016&category=ALL&country=ALL|work=KOFIC|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=Yearly BoxOffice [2016]}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, the distribution of the film was handled by Amazon Studios and [[Magnolia Pictures]]. The film opened in [[limited release]] across five cinemas in [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2016/10/arthouse-audit-moonlight-box-office-record-the-handmaiden-1201739455/|work=[[Indiewire]]|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=Arthouse Audit: \u2018Moonlight\u2019 Soars to Near-Record Levels; \u2018The Handmaiden\u2019 Beats the Odds|date=October 23, 2016|first=Brueggemann|last=Tom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/10/moonlight-king-cobra-michael-moore-trumpland-specialty-box-office-1201841247/|work=Deadline|accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=\u2018Moonlight\u2019 & \u2018Michael Moore In TrumpLand\u2019 Top 2016 Theater Averages \u2013 Specialty B.O.|date=October 23, 2016|first=Brooks|last=Brian}}</ref> and played in 140 additional cinemas in the following weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreadailyus.com/park-chan-wooks-new-erotic-thriller-the-handmaiden-opens-in-us-theaters/|work=The Korea Daily |accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=Park Chan-wook\u2019s New Erotic Thriller, The Handmaiden, Opens in US Theaters|date=October 21, 2016|first=Kim|last=Heewon}}</ref> Eventually, the film grossed more than $2 million in the United States theatrically;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=thehandmaiden.htm|title=The Handmaiden (2016)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> the film outgrossed ''[[Stoker (film)|Stoker]]'' and became the highest-grossing Park Chan-wook-directed film in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=stoker.htm|title=Stoker (2013) - Box Office Mojo|website=Boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>  It was released on DVD in the US on 24 January 2017 and Blu-ray on March 28, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flavorwire.com/597707/the-5-best-movies-to-buy-or-stream-this-week-the-handmaiden-the-light-between-oceans|work=Flavorwire |accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=The 5 Best Movies to Buy or Stream This Week: \u2018The Handmaiden,\u2019 \u2018The Man Who Fell to Earth\u2019|date=January 24, 2017|first=Bailey|last= Jason}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/8313/the-handmaiden|work=Dvdsreleasedates |accessdate=March 14, 2017|title=The Handmaiden (2016)}}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, the distribution of the film was handled by Amazon Studios and [[Curzon Artificial Eye]]. The film grossed more than $1.8 million in the United Kingdom theatrically, and became the highest-grossing foreign-language film in the UK in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/features/uk-box-office-2017-verdict-a-strong-year-despite-us-downturn/5125146.article|title=UK box office 2017 verdict: a strong year despite US downturn|publisher=|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n===Critical response===\n''The Handmaiden'' received critical acclaim. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an [[approval rating]] of 95%, based on 206 reviews, and an average score of 8.3/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''The Handmaiden'' uses a Victorian crime novel as the loose inspiration for another visually sumptuous and absorbingly idiosyncratic outing from director Park Chan-wook.\"<ref name=\"Rotten\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_handmaiden/|title=The Handmaiden|accessdate=23 November 2018|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds a [[weighted average]] score of 84 out of 100, based on 40 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-handmaiden|title=The Handmaiden|accessdate=3 July 2017|website=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref> ''[[The Economist]]'' described the film as a masterpiece.<ref name=\"economistreview\">{{cite news|author1=K.S.C.|title=\"The Handmaiden\": a new masterpiece from Park Chan-wook|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2017/04/korean-film|accessdate=17 April 2017|work=[[The Economist]]|date=13 April 2017}}</ref> Benjamin Lee of ''[[The Guardian]]'' ranked it four out of five stars and described it as \"a hugely entertaining thriller\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Lee, Benjamin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/may/14/the-handmaiden-review-park-chan-wooks-lurid-lesbian-potboiler-simmers-with-sexual-tension|title=The Handmaiden review \u2013 Park Chan-wook's lurid lesbian potboiler simmers with sexual tension |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=2016-05-14|accessdate=2018-11-16}}</ref>\n\n===Response to the explicit scenes===\nThe film's numerous sexually explicit scenes between the two main female characters sparked some controversy. Laura Miller at ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' described the scenes as \"disappointingly boilerplate\" and featuring \"visual clich\u00e9s of pornographic lesbianism, [the actresses'] bodies offered up for the camera\u2019s delectation.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Laura|title=The Handmaiden Park Chan-wook takes on Sarah Waters\u2019 brilliant, intricate novel Fingersmith|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/movies/2016/10/park_chan_wook_s_the_handmaiden_based_on_sarah_waters_fingersmith_reviewed.html|website=Slate|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref> However, The [[New Yorker (magazine)|''New Yorker'']]'s Jia Tolentino said that \"the women know what they look like, it seems\u2014they are consciously performing for each other\u2014and Park is deft at extracting the particular sense of silly freedom that can be found in enacting a sexual clich\u00e9.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tolentino|first1=Jia|title=\"The Handmaiden\" and the Freedom Women Find Only with One Another|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/jia-tolentino/the-handmaiden-and-the-freedom-women-find-only-with-one-another|accessdate=3 December 2017|agency=The New Yorker|publisher=Conde Nast|date=2016-10-26}}</ref>\n\n===Top ten lists===\n''The Handmaiden'' was listed on numerous critics' top ten lists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-list-the-top-10-movies-of-2016|title=Best of 2016: Film Critic Top Ten Lists|website=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* 1st&nbsp;\u2013 Danny Bowes, ''[[RogerEbert.com]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Dan Callahan, ''RogerEbert.com''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Noel Murray & Katie Rife, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Rob Hunter, ''[[Film School Rejects]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Sean Mulvihill, ''RogerEbert.com''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 Tasha Robinson, ''[[The Verge]]''\n* 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 William Bibbiani, ''[[CraveOnline]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 Amy Nicholson, ''[[MTV]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 Witney Seibold, ''[[CraveOnline]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 Jen Yamato, ''[[The Daily Beast]]''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 [[James Berardinelli]], ''Reelviews''\n* 3rd&nbsp;\u2013 [[Bilge Ebiri]], ''[[L.A. Weekly]]''\n* 4th&nbsp;\u2013 Kimberley Jones, ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''\n* 4th&nbsp;\u2013 Scott Tobias, ''[[Village Voice]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/filmpoll/view/critics/Scott+Tobias/2016 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-02-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170205182012/http://www.villagevoice.com/filmpoll/view/critics/Scott%2BTobias/2016 |archive-date=2017-02-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Lean Pickett, ''[[Chicago Reader]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Kate Taylor, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Josh Kupecki, ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Haleigh Foutch, ''[[Collider (website)|Collider]]''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Erin Whitney, ''ScreenCrush''\n* 5th&nbsp;\u2013 Peter Freeman, ''DC Outlook<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dcoutlook.com/2016/12/dc-outlooks-top-10-movies-of-2016.html|title=DC Outlook's Top 10 Movies of 2016|website=Dcoutlook.com|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref>''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 Sean Axmaker, ''Parallax View''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 John Powers, ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Alonso Duralde]], ''[[TheWrap]]''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Christy Lemire]] and Peter Sobczynski, ''RogerEbert.com''\n* 6th&nbsp;\u2013 Mike D\u2019Angelo & A.A. Dowd, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n* 7th&nbsp;\u2013 Bill Goodykoontz, ''[[The Arizona Republic]]''\n* 7th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Matt Zoller Seitz]] & Brian Tallerico, ''RogerEbert.com''\n* 7th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Christopher Orr (film critic)|Christopher Orr]], ''[[The Atlantic]]''\n* 7th&nbsp;\u2013 Steve Davis, ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013 Matt Singer, ''ScreenCrush''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Ty Burr]], ''[[The Boston Globe]]''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Todd McCarthy]], ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013 [[Manohla Dargis]], ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* 8th&nbsp;\u2013 [[David Edelstein]], ''[[New York Magazine]]''\n* 9th&nbsp;\u2013 ''[[The Guardian]]''\n* 10th&nbsp;\u2013 Marc Savlov, ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]''\n* 10th&nbsp;\u2013 Dennis Dermody, ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]''\n* Top 10 (listed alphabetically, not ranked)&nbsp;\u2013  Walter Addiego, ''San Francisco Chronicle''\n{{div col end}}\n\nIn 2019, ''[[The Guardian]]'' ranked ''The Handmaiden'' 41st in its 100 best films of the 21st century list.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 100 best films of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/sep/13/100-best-films-movies-of-the-21st-century |website=The Guardian |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref> In 2020, ''The Guardian'' also ranked it number 1 among the classics of modern South Korean Cinema.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|title=Classics of modern South Korean cinema \u2013 ranked! |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/feb/13/classics-of-modern-south-korean-cinema-ranked |website=The Guardian |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"| List of awards and nominations\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"62\"| 2016\n| [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://awfj.org/eda-awards-2/2016-awfj-eda-award-nominees/ |title=2016 AWFJ EDA Award Nominees |first=Jennifer |last=Merin |publisher=[[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]] |date=December 16, 2016 |accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wearemoviegeeks.com/2016/12/arrival-la-la-land-hell-high-water-among-nominees-2016-awfj-eda-awards/ |title='Arrival', 'La La Land', 'Hell or High Water' Among The Nominees for the 2016 AWFJ EDA Awards |first=Michelle |last=McCue |publisher=WeAreMovieGeeks.com |date=December 16, 2016 |accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n| Best Non-English-Language Film\n| [[Park Chan-wook]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[Austin Film Critics Association Awards 2016|Austin Film Critics Association]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awardswatch.com/news/austin-film-critics-association-afca-nominations-the-handmaiden-lands-top-mentions-trevante-rhodes-double-nominated/ |title=Austin Film Critics Association (AFCA) Nominations: The Handmaiden Lands Top Mentions, Trevante Rhodes Double Nominated |first=Erik |last=Anderson |publisher=AwardsWatch.com |date=December 15, 2016 |accessdate=December 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/austin-film-critics-association/2016-nominations-5307a85b7c6a#.yjh64hs3i |title=2016 Austin Film Critics Awards Nominees, 'Moonlight' and 'Arrival' lead the way in AFCA's 2016 nominations |first=Neil |last=Miller |publisher=Medium.com |date=December 15, 2016 |accessdate=December 15, 2016}}</ref>\n| Best Film\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{draw|4th Place}}\n|-\n| Best Director\n| Park Chan-wook\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Supporting Actress\n| [[Kim Min-hee (actress, born 1982)|Kim Min-hee]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Adapted Screenplay\n| Park Chan-wook and Chung Seo-kyung\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Cinematography\n| Chung Chung-hoon\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Foreign Language Film\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[37th Blue Dragon Film Awards|Blue Dragon Film Awards]]\n| Best Film\n| ''The Handmaiden''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Director\n| Park Chan-wook\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actress\n| Kim Min-hee\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best New Actre